1
00:00:02,827 --> 00:00:05,827
[music playing]

2
00:00:32,724 --> 00:00:36,586
[horns sounding]

3
00:00:40,655 --> 00:00:44,517
[music playing]

4
00:01:26,620 --> 00:01:29,482
NARRATOR: In the
pleasant summer of 1914,

5
00:01:29,586 --> 00:01:32,172
the American community
was [inaudible],

6
00:01:32,275 --> 00:01:34,413
was finding it
easier and happier

7
00:01:34,517 --> 00:01:38,275
than ever before in its history.

8
00:01:38,379 --> 00:01:41,413
[trolley stopping]

9
00:01:55,793 --> 00:01:57,689
A Washington cream pie.

10
00:01:57,793 --> 00:01:58,689
Washington cream pie?

11
00:02:02,241 --> 00:02:04,275
You like it too, [inaudible]?

12
00:02:09,586 --> 00:02:12,862
NARRATOR: In America'sbrave little world of 1914,

13
00:02:12,965 --> 00:02:17,068
a self-contained and contented
people would look back

14
00:02:17,172 --> 00:02:18,482
with satisfaction
on nearly a century

15
00:02:18,586 --> 00:02:22,551
and a half of unparalleledprogress and prosperity.

16
00:02:41,206 --> 00:02:43,068
American industry
lead the world,

17
00:02:43,172 --> 00:02:46,862
and was rapidly
increasing its lead.

18
00:02:46,965 --> 00:02:50,379
To contribute to and share inthe wealth of a growing nation,

19
00:02:50,482 --> 00:02:51,965
immigrants from every
part of the world

20
00:02:52,068 --> 00:02:55,379
were still flocking
to US shores,

21
00:02:55,482 --> 00:02:58,344
bringing up their childrenin the American community as

22
00:02:58,448 --> 00:03:01,965
new first generation Americans.

23
00:03:02,068 --> 00:03:04,517
[children chattering]

24
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:09,862
[bell ringing]

25
00:03:14,758 --> 00:03:17,310
Most communities
of any size in 1914

26
00:03:17,413 --> 00:03:19,724
could boast of their
own daily newspaper,

27
00:03:19,827 --> 00:03:23,344
whose editor championed
their causes,

28
00:03:23,448 --> 00:03:25,379
helped fight their battles.

29
00:03:25,482 --> 00:03:28,793
But Americans of 1914 werelittle interested in news

30
00:03:28,896 --> 00:03:32,482
outside their own communityand their own nation.

31
00:03:38,793 --> 00:03:41,931
The country was still debatingafter two years the merits

32
00:03:42,034 --> 00:03:45,068
of the New Freedom,slogan of Woodrow Wilson,

33
00:03:45,172 --> 00:03:46,965
the first Democrat
to occupy the White

34
00:03:47,068 --> 00:03:47,931
House since Grover Cleveland.

35
00:03:52,137 --> 00:03:56,620
The Panama Canal, in whichthe whole nation took pride,

36
00:03:56,724 --> 00:03:58,482
was scheduled finally to
be opened in mid August.

37
00:04:01,862 --> 00:04:04,827
And the man most responsiblefor the canal, ex-president

38
00:04:04,931 --> 00:04:07,896
Theodore Roosevelt, was
still a powerful figure

39
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:08,862
on the US political scene.

40
00:04:13,586 --> 00:04:15,068
The regular Army of
the United States

41
00:04:15,172 --> 00:04:19,000
totaled just under 100,000men in the summer of 1914,

42
00:04:19,103 --> 00:04:22,517
and many a US citizen feltthat even this number was

43
00:04:22,620 --> 00:04:24,448
excessive for a force
that had little to do

44
00:04:24,551 --> 00:04:26,000
but chase Mexican bandits.

45
00:04:28,862 --> 00:04:31,931
Heavier than aircraft
were undergoing tests

46
00:04:32,034 --> 00:04:35,310
by a few young andfar-sighted army officers,

47
00:04:35,413 --> 00:04:37,689
who hoped eventually to
put the new invention to

48
00:04:37,793 --> 00:04:38,862
some useful military purpose.

49
00:04:42,103 --> 00:04:45,517
Fast achieving popularitywas the Hesitation

50
00:04:45,620 --> 00:04:49,620
Canter, a startling newoutgrowth of the Turkey trot.

51
00:05:04,896 --> 00:05:07,206
In 1914, young
citizens of America

52
00:05:07,310 --> 00:05:10,965
were looking forward with highhope for the future of a land

53
00:05:11,068 --> 00:05:12,379
which was still a new world.

54
00:05:12,482 --> 00:05:14,758
It was a settled
and ordered world,

55
00:05:14,862 --> 00:05:17,931
in which youth,
keen and confident,

56
00:05:18,034 --> 00:05:19,517
saw limitless opportunity.

57
00:05:25,827 --> 00:05:29,068
There were new standards andnew ideals, new entertain

58
00:05:29,172 --> 00:05:31,275
and new pleasures.

59
00:05:31,379 --> 00:05:33,275
Well, just as the
train came to a trestle,

60
00:05:33,379 --> 00:05:35,586
she got to the window
and jumped out.

61
00:05:35,689 --> 00:05:36,793
Well?

62
00:05:36,896 --> 00:05:38,931
Well, that's the way it
ended until next week.

63
00:05:39,034 --> 00:05:39,896
Isn't that just like them?

64
00:05:46,137 --> 00:05:49,620
NARRATOR: An earnest people,living in a land grown

65
00:05:49,724 --> 00:05:53,379
powerful and great, wereonly beginning to realize how

66
00:05:53,482 --> 00:05:56,137
truly great their nation was.

67
00:05:56,241 --> 00:05:59,655
[train whistle]

68
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,517
Until the arrival of thepaper train on the morning

69
00:06:09,620 --> 00:06:14,206
of June 1914, Europe
and Europe's troubles

70
00:06:14,310 --> 00:06:15,896
seemed very far away.

71
00:06:20,206 --> 00:06:27,379
Say, Harry, is an Archduke likea prince, or is he like a king?

72
00:06:27,482 --> 00:06:30,344
Search me.

73
00:06:30,448 --> 00:06:32,068
[train whistle]

74
00:06:33,034 --> 00:06:36,827
[bells]

75
00:07:02,620 --> 00:07:04,310
NARRATOR: In the days
that quickly followed

76
00:07:04,413 --> 00:07:07,517
the first declaration ofwar, as country after country

77
00:07:07,620 --> 00:07:11,310
mobilized and marched, the
news that mattered most

78
00:07:11,413 --> 00:07:14,655
was the news of Europe andits spreading battle fronts.

79
00:07:20,310 --> 00:07:23,413
It was America's foreign-bornwho first felt the impact

80
00:07:23,517 --> 00:07:24,896
of the war in Europe.

81
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:26,724
And they tried as best
they could to explain

82
00:07:26,827 --> 00:07:29,068
it to their American friends.

83
00:07:29,172 --> 00:07:31,931
To them, war was a
sad, familiar Old

84
00:07:32,034 --> 00:07:36,586
World story, the age-old uponthe lands from which they came.

85
00:07:36,689 --> 00:07:40,344
Anna, [inaudible], look.

86
00:07:40,448 --> 00:07:41,206
Right here in the paper.

87
00:07:44,655 --> 00:07:47,103
[galloping]

88
00:07:53,620 --> 00:07:55,758
[door bell]

89
00:08:00,620 --> 00:08:03,137
A registered letter
for you, Mrs. Kovacs.

90
00:08:03,241 --> 00:08:06,241
Looks like something
from the old country.

91
00:08:06,344 --> 00:08:07,344
You can sign for it.

92
00:08:11,724 --> 00:08:13,620
It'd be odd to sign for this.

93
00:08:13,724 --> 00:08:15,655
You don't want me to bringit back again, do you?

94
00:08:15,758 --> 00:08:16,689
Sign right here.

95
00:08:22,586 --> 00:08:23,310
Thank you.

96
00:08:23,413 --> 00:08:24,137
Goodbye.

97
00:08:29,413 --> 00:08:32,862
[train whistle]

98
00:08:37,758 --> 00:08:38,620
Hello, Anna.

99
00:08:38,724 --> 00:08:40,551
What are you doing here?

100
00:08:40,655 --> 00:08:42,793
Joe, the postman
brought it this morning.

101
00:08:49,482 --> 00:08:53,379
What does it say, Joe?

102
00:08:53,482 --> 00:08:55,862
It's for the army.

103
00:08:55,965 --> 00:09:00,344
We'll talk it over
when we get home, Mama.

104
00:09:00,448 --> 00:09:03,379
[buoyant music]

105
00:09:16,896 --> 00:09:18,517
Any from Austria?

106
00:09:18,620 --> 00:09:20,310
I don't know
where they're from,

107
00:09:20,413 --> 00:09:24,551
the "Pathe Weekly" is on now.

108
00:09:24,655 --> 00:09:29,758
[music playing]

109
00:11:16,931 --> 00:11:19,137
[non-english speech]

110
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:27,344
You got Army papers
too, huh, John?

111
00:11:27,448 --> 00:11:29,551
Yeah, come today.

112
00:11:29,655 --> 00:11:31,241
What's your take?

113
00:11:31,344 --> 00:11:32,379
Not for me.

114
00:11:32,482 --> 00:11:34,068
That's Old Country business.

115
00:11:34,172 --> 00:11:36,689
I'm staying in America
with the wife and kids.

116
00:11:36,793 --> 00:11:37,758
What you going to do?

117
00:11:40,344 --> 00:11:44,172
If you don't go now, you'llnever get back to Old Country.

118
00:11:44,275 --> 00:11:46,172
I go Monday, maybe.

119
00:11:46,275 --> 00:11:48,000
Joe.

120
00:11:48,103 --> 00:11:51,551
Now, Mama, in times
like this, a man's got

121
00:11:51,655 --> 00:11:53,137
to do what he thinks is right.

122
00:12:21,896 --> 00:12:25,310
[speaking german]

123
00:12:30,103 --> 00:12:31,137
When do you go, Joe?

124
00:12:33,931 --> 00:12:36,758
I take the train for
New York this afternoon.

125
00:12:36,862 --> 00:12:40,448
Did you ask them
about the money?

126
00:12:40,551 --> 00:12:44,172
Well, Anna, they said
it's hard to get money

127
00:12:44,275 --> 00:12:46,137
through from the
Old Country now.

128
00:12:46,241 --> 00:12:49,517
What are we going to live on?

129
00:12:49,620 --> 00:12:50,517
Oh, Papa.

130
00:12:50,620 --> 00:12:51,344
I'm sorry.

131
00:12:54,379 --> 00:12:55,103
Come, we go.

132
00:13:03,103 --> 00:13:05,344
NARRATOR: With the invasionof neutral Belgium,

133
00:13:05,448 --> 00:13:08,206
Americans awoke to the fulland terrible implications

134
00:13:08,310 --> 00:13:09,068
of a modern war.

135
00:13:13,965 --> 00:13:16,241
A taxi cab army,
rushed from Paris,

136
00:13:16,344 --> 00:13:19,000
brought the miracle
of the Marne.

137
00:13:24,275 --> 00:13:27,827
Britain's contemptibles,as the Kaiser called them,

138
00:13:27,931 --> 00:13:30,068
were desperately holding
the Flanders' front.

139
00:13:41,551 --> 00:13:44,448
American military men knewthat Germany had devoted all

140
00:13:44,551 --> 00:13:48,000
her energies for 20 years tobuilding up the greatest war

141
00:13:48,103 --> 00:13:51,344
machine the world had everseen, armies that were now

142
00:13:51,448 --> 00:13:54,000
systematically destroyingin their advance

143
00:13:54,103 --> 00:13:56,103
the towns, the cities,
and the homes of

144
00:13:56,206 --> 00:13:58,137
a simple, peace-loving people.

145
00:14:08,068 --> 00:14:10,965
And there were signs in
the American community

146
00:14:11,068 --> 00:14:14,620
that the nation was aroused.

147
00:14:14,724 --> 00:14:16,137
Razor all right, Congressman?

148
00:14:16,241 --> 00:14:16,965
Mm-mm.

149
00:14:20,827 --> 00:14:22,689
John, I'm not
going to find it so

150
00:14:22,793 --> 00:14:25,517
easy to be neutral in thought.

151
00:14:25,620 --> 00:14:26,344
JOHN: Mm-mm.

152
00:14:33,103 --> 00:14:34,724
NARRATOR: Already,
the war in Europe

153
00:14:34,827 --> 00:14:38,931
was finding its way into theeveryday lives of Americans.

154
00:14:39,034 --> 00:14:40,000
Americans of every age.

155
00:14:43,586 --> 00:14:44,482
H2O.

156
00:14:44,586 --> 00:14:47,517
Twice, please Anna.

157
00:14:47,620 --> 00:14:51,275
Say, I'm sorry to hear thatyou're quitting school.

158
00:14:51,379 --> 00:14:52,724
Do you have to?

159
00:14:52,827 --> 00:14:54,413
What else can I do?

160
00:14:54,517 --> 00:14:56,896
I've got to help Mother.

161
00:14:57,000 --> 00:14:59,689
I don't understand
Pop doing what he did.

162
00:14:59,793 --> 00:15:03,344
Well, I suppose you can't blameanybody for being patriotic.

163
00:15:03,448 --> 00:15:05,034
But he didn't have
to go over there.

164
00:15:05,137 --> 00:15:07,000
It wasn't his war.

165
00:15:07,103 --> 00:15:08,896
The war will be over ina couple of months anyway.

166
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:10,068
That's what my
father says, and he

167
00:15:10,172 --> 00:15:11,620
used to be in the German army.

168
00:15:11,724 --> 00:15:15,965
I suppose he thinks theGermans are going to win.

169
00:15:16,068 --> 00:15:19,206
They win every day, don't they?

170
00:15:19,310 --> 00:15:20,931
If your old man
likes Germany so much,

171
00:15:21,034 --> 00:15:23,206
he'd better go back there.

172
00:15:23,310 --> 00:15:24,620
That goes for you go too.

173
00:15:24,724 --> 00:15:26,965
Never mind him, Freddy.

174
00:15:27,068 --> 00:15:28,241
Don't let that
guy get your goat.

175
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:45,137
The army advanced
along the whole front

176
00:15:45,241 --> 00:15:50,448
again today, in some placesnearly five kilometers.

177
00:15:50,551 --> 00:15:52,448
You're not eating
much tonight, Fred.

178
00:15:52,551 --> 00:15:53,448
What's the matter?

179
00:15:53,551 --> 00:15:54,965
Nothing Mama, I'm
just not hungry.

180
00:15:55,068 --> 00:15:57,586
Anna Kovacs has
had to quit school.

181
00:15:57,689 --> 00:15:59,965
Her father's been called
by the Austrian army,

182
00:16:00,068 --> 00:16:01,896
and now she has to work.

183
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:04,413
So?

184
00:16:04,517 --> 00:16:07,758
Dad, it's getting
so that all of you

185
00:16:07,862 --> 00:16:11,241
and everybody else talk aboutis this war all the time.

186
00:16:11,344 --> 00:16:13,241
Today, I said that you hadbeen in the German army,

187
00:16:13,344 --> 00:16:15,965
and that you thought theGermans would win in two months.

188
00:16:16,068 --> 00:16:17,275
I didn't mean anything.

189
00:16:17,379 --> 00:16:21,620
It almost started a
free-for-all, Father.

190
00:16:21,724 --> 00:16:24,034
That's too bad, Frederick.

191
00:16:24,137 --> 00:16:27,241
Perhaps I should
be more careful.

192
00:16:27,344 --> 00:16:30,793
It is very wrong for any ofus to get personally agitated

193
00:16:30,896 --> 00:16:32,586
about the wars of far away.

194
00:16:32,689 --> 00:16:34,448
We are in American.

195
00:16:34,551 --> 00:16:37,793
President Wilson said,
this is a war with which

196
00:16:37,896 --> 00:16:40,206
we have nothing to do.

197
00:16:40,310 --> 00:16:42,310
That is how we all
must try to feel.

198
00:16:45,965 --> 00:16:50,275
NARRATOR: Under the personalcommand of Kaiser Wilhelm II,

199
00:16:50,379 --> 00:16:53,206
the armies of imperialGermany seemed invincible

200
00:16:53,310 --> 00:16:55,689
in the summer of 1914.

201
00:16:55,793 --> 00:16:59,448
And Americans began to realizethat belief in a just cause

202
00:16:59,551 --> 00:17:02,620
was not enough against
superior manpower

203
00:17:02,724 --> 00:17:03,655
and superior armaments.

204
00:17:08,965 --> 00:17:13,172
The bravery of the Belgians,fighting on To hold the channel

205
00:17:13,275 --> 00:17:16,137
ports, further heightenedAmerica's desire

206
00:17:16,241 --> 00:17:17,793
to help these stricken people.

207
00:17:24,862 --> 00:17:29,344
Most Americans feel that
the invasion of Belgium

208
00:17:29,448 --> 00:17:31,655
was the most barbarous
act ever committed

209
00:17:31,758 --> 00:17:33,793
by a civilized nation.

210
00:17:33,896 --> 00:17:36,586
[applause]

211
00:17:36,689 --> 00:17:38,344
We are not here to
discuss the rights

212
00:17:38,448 --> 00:17:40,931
and wrongs of the European war.

213
00:17:41,034 --> 00:17:46,172
We are here to help its innocentvictims, little children,

214
00:17:46,275 --> 00:17:48,655
helpless and starving.

215
00:17:48,758 --> 00:17:51,689
The Committee for the Reliefof Belgium under the able

216
00:17:51,793 --> 00:17:57,275
chairmanship of Herbert Hoover,can feed a Belgian child

217
00:17:57,379 --> 00:18:02,275
for a month on a $5 bill.

218
00:18:02,379 --> 00:18:07,034
It is up to us to see thathe gets those $5 bills.

219
00:18:07,137 --> 00:18:11,517
Yes, and $10s, and
$20s, and $50s.

220
00:18:11,620 --> 00:18:13,551
NARRATOR: A generous
people had assumed

221
00:18:13,655 --> 00:18:16,137
its first responsibility
of the war,

222
00:18:16,241 --> 00:18:19,551
with the help of a young miningengineer named Herbert Hoover.

223
00:18:22,206 --> 00:18:24,275
Within three months, he
had organized a fleet

224
00:18:24,379 --> 00:18:27,241
of 35 vessels, carrying
more than a million

225
00:18:27,344 --> 00:18:29,310
worth of food a week to Belgium.

226
00:18:38,413 --> 00:18:40,931
As the war entered
its first winter,

227
00:18:41,034 --> 00:18:43,517
American contributions werekeeping alive 10 million

228
00:18:43,620 --> 00:18:46,172
homeless, starving
people, helpless wards

229
00:18:46,275 --> 00:18:49,620
of the one nation of the
world still able to feed

230
00:18:49,724 --> 00:18:50,724
and care for them.

231
00:18:59,586 --> 00:19:02,827
Aren't these
Professor Carter's?

232
00:19:02,931 --> 00:19:04,586
Why, of course they are.

233
00:19:04,689 --> 00:19:07,896
Do you suppose he'sreally bought a new suit?

234
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:10,413
We can't send these old
things to the Belgians

235
00:19:10,517 --> 00:19:12,931
with St. Luke's name on them.

236
00:19:13,034 --> 00:19:15,689
And those poor Belgian women.

237
00:19:15,793 --> 00:19:19,275
--[sighing] I can't
bear to think of them.

238
00:19:19,379 --> 00:19:21,931
Well, I just can't
understand it.

239
00:19:22,034 --> 00:19:23,103
Why, Dora.

240
00:19:23,206 --> 00:19:25,172
We all know German people.

241
00:19:25,275 --> 00:19:28,000
Some of us have German friends.

242
00:19:28,103 --> 00:19:29,379
Look at the Bensingers.

243
00:19:29,482 --> 00:19:31,758
They're as nice as
anybody could be.

244
00:19:35,275 --> 00:19:37,000
NARRATOR: --with Europe's war.

245
00:19:37,103 --> 00:19:39,965
America was a neutralnation, but neutral nations

246
00:19:40,068 --> 00:19:42,862
on the high seas were beingopenly and flagrantly violated

247
00:19:42,965 --> 00:19:44,275
by Germany.

248
00:19:44,379 --> 00:19:47,655
What a way for a civilizednation to fight a war.

249
00:19:47,758 --> 00:19:49,482
Why shouldn't they
sink English ships?

250
00:19:49,586 --> 00:19:51,448
So why don't the
submarines give

251
00:19:51,551 --> 00:19:53,482
warning, so the crews
will have a chance

252
00:19:53,586 --> 00:19:55,034
to get into life boats.

253
00:19:55,137 --> 00:19:57,827
The Germans have got to sinkships if they're carrying

254
00:19:57,931 --> 00:20:00,172
munitions for the Allies.

255
00:20:00,275 --> 00:20:02,137
And suppose they have
Americans on them?

256
00:20:02,241 --> 00:20:03,344
They shouldn't be there.

257
00:20:03,448 --> 00:20:04,793
The German government
has warned them.

258
00:20:04,896 --> 00:20:06,068
[audio out] be there.

259
00:20:06,172 --> 00:20:06,965
Huh.

260
00:20:07,068 --> 00:20:09,000
Don't make me--

261
00:20:12,896 --> 00:20:15,793
NARRATOR: But far more
fateful [audio out]

262
00:20:15,896 --> 00:20:19,482
questions of international lawwas the submarines' steadily

263
00:20:19,586 --> 00:20:21,896
mounting toll of human lives.

264
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:24,758
[music playing]

265
00:20:27,206 --> 00:20:29,413
Men like Theodore
Roosevelt were now

266
00:20:29,517 --> 00:20:31,482
demanding forceful
action to uphold

267
00:20:31,586 --> 00:20:34,896
the nation's traditional
freedom of the seas.

268
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:37,137
But few Americans wouldbelieve that their rights

269
00:20:37,241 --> 00:20:38,655
were seriously threatened.

270
00:20:43,137 --> 00:20:46,000
[typing]

271
00:20:47,103 --> 00:20:48,965
Clarence.

272
00:20:49,068 --> 00:20:51,551
[typing]

273
00:20:52,517 --> 00:20:55,068
And they sunk the "Lusitania."

274
00:20:55,172 --> 00:20:55,931
What?

275
00:21:04,827 --> 00:21:06,896
Tell circulation we
have an extra coming on.

276
00:21:13,379 --> 00:21:14,931
How many Americans aboard?

277
00:21:15,034 --> 00:21:19,275
228.

278
00:21:19,379 --> 00:21:21,275
96-point banner.

279
00:21:21,379 --> 00:21:22,862
Play up the American angle.

280
00:21:30,241 --> 00:21:32,758
The Germans had run a warningto "Lusitania" passengers.

281
00:21:32,862 --> 00:21:33,620
What do you mean?

282
00:21:33,724 --> 00:21:35,344
An ad in "The New York Times."

283
00:21:35,448 --> 00:21:36,241
In "The Times?"

284
00:21:36,344 --> 00:21:37,068
Have you got a copy?

285
00:21:43,413 --> 00:21:46,724
I didn't think they'd
dare to sink her.

286
00:21:46,827 --> 00:21:48,586
The warning of
the German embassy

287
00:21:48,689 --> 00:21:50,517
had attracted little notice.

288
00:21:50,620 --> 00:21:54,517
It was unthinkable that Germanywould sink the "Lusitania."

289
00:21:54,620 --> 00:21:57,862
Her sailing had been set
for a Saturday for noon.

290
00:21:57,965 --> 00:22:01,620
On her passenger list were someof the proudest names of two

291
00:22:01,724 --> 00:22:04,103
continents, for the
"Lusitania" was queen

292
00:22:04,206 --> 00:22:06,724
of the great [inaudible] fleet.

293
00:22:06,827 --> 00:22:08,862
It was to be a gay
and festive voyage.

294
00:22:20,275 --> 00:22:24,551
Nearly 2,000 souls were aboard.

295
00:22:24,655 --> 00:22:26,931
1,200 never reached shore.

296
00:22:27,034 --> 00:22:30,103
No single disaster
in half a century

297
00:22:30,206 --> 00:22:33,034
had stirred Americanemotions more profoundly.

298
00:22:46,862 --> 00:22:49,931
If Wilson stands for this,he'll stand for anything.

299
00:22:50,034 --> 00:22:51,310
Stand for what?

300
00:22:51,413 --> 00:22:52,310
Stand for murder.

301
00:22:52,413 --> 00:22:54,793
Murder of 114 Americans.

302
00:22:54,896 --> 00:22:55,827
[inaudible].

303
00:22:55,931 --> 00:22:57,034
MAN: An American
citizen has the right

304
00:22:57,137 --> 00:22:58,689
to travel anywhere he wants to.

305
00:22:58,793 --> 00:23:01,620
We oughta lick the Kaisernow and have it over with.

306
00:23:01,724 --> 00:23:03,413
You're gonna have a
hard time [audio out].

307
00:23:03,517 --> 00:23:05,689
They don't care how many
Americans get killed.

308
00:23:05,793 --> 00:23:07,793
And what do they say
about the "Lusitania."

309
00:23:07,896 --> 00:23:10,551
Well, in Montana, they thinkif a man goes out in the street

310
00:23:10,655 --> 00:23:12,206
when there's shooting
going on, it's

311
00:23:12,310 --> 00:23:14,965
his own fault if he gets hit.

312
00:23:15,068 --> 00:23:18,965
[band playing]

313
00:24:00,241 --> 00:24:03,137
[church bells]

314
00:24:06,689 --> 00:24:10,586
NARRATOR: Anger and indignation,deep and mounting, swept

315
00:24:10,689 --> 00:24:13,620
every community in the land.

316
00:24:13,724 --> 00:24:15,896
Throughout the nation on
the following Sabbath,

317
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:18,724
there were memorial
services for the men,

318
00:24:18,827 --> 00:24:21,344
the women, and the childrenwho were the "Lusitania's"

319
00:24:21,448 --> 00:24:23,241
martyred dead.

320
00:24:23,344 --> 00:24:25,689
[galloping]

321
00:24:30,413 --> 00:24:34,344
Well, boys, what's
on your mind?

322
00:24:34,448 --> 00:24:35,551
We came to find out
what you're going

323
00:24:35,655 --> 00:24:37,655
to do about the "Lusitania."

324
00:24:37,758 --> 00:24:40,448
To tell the truth, I hadn'tthought of doing anything.

325
00:24:40,551 --> 00:24:42,689
John, you're our Congressman.

326
00:24:42,793 --> 00:24:44,724
You know how they're feeling.

327
00:24:44,827 --> 00:24:47,310
Don't you think you oughtto go talk with President

328
00:24:47,413 --> 00:24:49,931
Wilson about this thing?

329
00:24:50,034 --> 00:24:52,931
Well, now boys, you don'twalk in on the President

330
00:24:53,034 --> 00:24:54,241
just that way.

331
00:24:54,344 --> 00:24:55,827
He's already said
he would Germany

332
00:24:55,931 --> 00:24:57,862
to strict accountability.

333
00:24:57,965 --> 00:25:00,241
John, we've been hearingabout strict accountability

334
00:25:00,344 --> 00:25:02,965
for a long time.

335
00:25:03,068 --> 00:25:05,241
It seems to mean that
when a German U-boat

336
00:25:05,344 --> 00:25:07,482
kills some more Americans,the President just

337
00:25:07,586 --> 00:25:09,172
sends another note.

338
00:25:09,275 --> 00:25:11,724
What do you want to do?

339
00:25:11,827 --> 00:25:14,965
You ought to go to Wilson,and tell him he's got to act,

340
00:25:15,068 --> 00:25:17,344
and act quick.

341
00:25:17,448 --> 00:25:19,482
All right.

342
00:25:19,586 --> 00:25:22,862
I can go to Wilson.

343
00:25:22,965 --> 00:25:25,310
Are you boys willing
to go to war?

344
00:25:25,413 --> 00:25:29,379
That's not the point John,and you know it isn't.

345
00:25:29,482 --> 00:25:31,931
The point is you
want to do something,

346
00:25:32,034 --> 00:25:35,068
but you don't want to do theonly thing the Germans would

347
00:25:35,172 --> 00:25:35,896
understand, war.

348
00:25:42,310 --> 00:25:44,310
this country isn't
ready to fight a war,

349
00:25:44,413 --> 00:25:46,620
even if it wanted to.

350
00:25:46,724 --> 00:25:50,068
Just suppose I do
go to the President?

351
00:25:50,172 --> 00:25:55,172
Suppose he says, all right, ifyou want a war, you'll get it.

352
00:25:55,275 --> 00:25:58,137
Do you want your boy
to go to war, Ed?

353
00:26:01,241 --> 00:26:04,103
Will you fight?

354
00:26:04,206 --> 00:26:05,724
I know how you feel.

355
00:26:05,827 --> 00:26:08,344
I feel the same way.

356
00:26:08,448 --> 00:26:11,172
But it's war or nothing.

357
00:26:11,275 --> 00:26:16,724
And I still think it
ought to be nothing.

358
00:26:16,827 --> 00:26:21,000
NARRATOR:US opinion was
still deeply divided.

359
00:26:21,103 --> 00:26:24,793
To demands for action,
Woodrow Wilton answered,

360
00:26:24,896 --> 00:26:26,413
there is such a
thing as a nation

361
00:26:26,517 --> 00:26:28,931
being too proud to fight.

362
00:26:29,034 --> 00:26:31,000
It was a bitterly
disputed phrase.

363
00:26:35,206 --> 00:26:39,413
But other US citizens
were going to war.

364
00:26:39,517 --> 00:26:42,551
Across the border, thousands ofyou Americans of military age

365
00:26:42,655 --> 00:26:46,241
were joining famed Canadianregiments-- the Black Watch

366
00:26:46,344 --> 00:26:50,620
and Princess Pats-- to fightalongside Canadians in a cause

367
00:26:50,724 --> 00:26:52,827
they believed to be just.

368
00:26:52,931 --> 00:26:56,000
[patriotic music]

369
00:27:03,965 --> 00:27:06,448
Bought and sent overseasby the contributions of US

370
00:27:06,551 --> 00:27:11,724
communities, driven by Americanswho paid their own expenses,

371
00:27:11,827 --> 00:27:14,655
nearly 100 ambulances
by the end of 1915

372
00:27:14,758 --> 00:27:17,137
were on the
battlefields of France.

373
00:27:25,827 --> 00:27:27,517
[plane engine]

374
00:27:27,620 --> 00:27:31,103
Bearing the name of a Frenchsoldier who had helped America

375
00:27:31,206 --> 00:27:34,275
to win her independence,
the Lafayette Escadrille

376
00:27:34,379 --> 00:27:37,413
was an elite corps
of US volunteers.

377
00:27:48,103 --> 00:27:49,758
[engine]

378
00:27:49,862 --> 00:27:52,034
[explosion]

379
00:27:56,310 --> 00:28:00,586
In the American community,emotion for the Allied cause

380
00:28:00,689 --> 00:28:02,586
was running high.

381
00:28:02,689 --> 00:28:04,689
And in a town as
important as this,

382
00:28:04,793 --> 00:28:09,206
with the mainline railroad, thereservoir, the college and all,

383
00:28:09,310 --> 00:28:11,724
they'd be sure to
have at least one spy.

384
00:28:11,827 --> 00:28:13,344
Honestly, Dora.

385
00:28:13,448 --> 00:28:18,103
Do you really believe ElizabethBensinger's husband is a spy?

386
00:28:18,206 --> 00:28:20,689
Where there's
smoke, there's fire.

387
00:28:20,793 --> 00:28:22,172
Hello, everybody.

388
00:28:22,275 --> 00:28:23,172
WOMEN: Hello.

389
00:28:23,275 --> 00:28:23,965
Hello.

390
00:28:24,068 --> 00:28:26,482
Hello, Mrs. Averill.

391
00:28:26,586 --> 00:28:27,310
Hello, Elizabeth.

392
00:28:27,413 --> 00:28:28,172
How are you?

393
00:28:28,275 --> 00:28:29,103
I'm fine.

394
00:28:29,206 --> 00:28:30,103
How are you?

395
00:28:30,206 --> 00:28:31,172
Elizabeth?

396
00:28:31,275 --> 00:28:32,344
Yes?

397
00:28:32,448 --> 00:28:34,241
May I speak to you and
Hilda a moment please?

398
00:28:34,344 --> 00:28:35,206
Why, certainly.

399
00:28:35,310 --> 00:28:36,034
Hilda?

400
00:28:40,551 --> 00:28:43,620
I thought I ought to tellyou that since we are working

401
00:28:43,724 --> 00:28:46,620
on bandages for
the Allies, we all

402
00:28:46,724 --> 00:28:50,931
feel that perhaps you andHilda could make yourselves

403
00:28:51,034 --> 00:28:53,310
more useful somewhere else.

404
00:28:53,413 --> 00:28:58,172
I'm not quite sure that Iunderstand what you mean, Dora.

405
00:28:58,275 --> 00:29:03,000
With feeling as it is aboutthe Germans, I'm very sorry.

406
00:29:03,103 --> 00:29:07,379
But I'm sure you will avoidunpleasantness if you go.

407
00:29:07,482 --> 00:29:08,206
Come, Hilda.

408
00:29:24,827 --> 00:29:27,896
[patriotic music]

409
00:29:33,586 --> 00:29:35,655
NARRATOR: In every
US community by 1915,

410
00:29:35,758 --> 00:29:38,413
the lines were
slowly being drawn

411
00:29:38,517 --> 00:29:44,413
between peace at any priceand intervention in the war.

412
00:29:44,517 --> 00:29:48,000
[crowd chattering]

413
00:29:58,827 --> 00:30:00,379
When I hear these
fools shouting

414
00:30:00,482 --> 00:30:06,137
about being too proud tofight, it makes my blood boil.

415
00:30:06,241 --> 00:30:08,241
Don't they know that
the Allies are fighting

416
00:30:08,344 --> 00:30:09,379
to save our own civilization?

417
00:30:13,862 --> 00:30:16,448
I'm glad you feel
that way, Dad.

418
00:30:16,551 --> 00:30:20,379
Because I want to jointhe Lafayette Escadrille.

419
00:30:20,482 --> 00:30:22,379
What?

420
00:30:22,482 --> 00:30:26,896
I want to join the LafayetteEscadrille and go to France.

421
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:30,241
Well, Walter, that's
a fine sentiment.

422
00:30:30,344 --> 00:30:32,931
But I'm afraid it
isn't very practical.

423
00:30:33,034 --> 00:30:35,413
You're hardly old enough
for a thing like that.

424
00:30:35,517 --> 00:30:37,448
Of course I am, Dad.

425
00:30:37,551 --> 00:30:40,758
They'll take you at 18.

426
00:30:40,862 --> 00:30:43,034
But Walter, what
about your college?

427
00:30:43,137 --> 00:30:45,172
Dad, how can I keep
my mind on studies

428
00:30:45,275 --> 00:30:47,172
with a war going on
that's going to affect

429
00:30:47,275 --> 00:30:50,448
the whole future of the world?

430
00:30:50,551 --> 00:30:53,379
You won't much voice in thefuture of the world, Walter,

431
00:30:53,482 --> 00:30:55,241
if you go over there
and don't come back.

432
00:30:57,793 --> 00:31:00,137
I'll have to take
a chance on that.

433
00:31:00,241 --> 00:31:02,068
A lot of other people have.

434
00:31:02,172 --> 00:31:04,551
[patriotic music]

435
00:31:14,068 --> 00:31:17,862
Why did you have totalk to me first, Walter?

436
00:31:17,965 --> 00:31:18,862
Well, it--

437
00:31:18,965 --> 00:31:20,896
Because my father's German?

438
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:23,482
Walter, I love my father.

439
00:31:23,586 --> 00:31:26,517
I'd do anything in theworld rather than hurt him,

440
00:31:26,620 --> 00:31:29,724
or let anybody hurt him.

441
00:31:29,827 --> 00:31:35,689
I know he wants the Germansto win the war, but I don't.

442
00:31:35,793 --> 00:31:37,965
What do you want, Hilda?

443
00:31:38,068 --> 00:31:42,965
I want you to go toFrance, if you want to go.

444
00:31:43,068 --> 00:31:45,310
I'd be proud of you, Walter.

445
00:31:48,827 --> 00:31:52,275
[train bells]

446
00:31:56,758 --> 00:31:57,655
So long, boy.

447
00:31:57,758 --> 00:31:58,482
Take care of yourself.

448
00:32:01,793 --> 00:32:03,655
You've been great, Dad.

449
00:32:03,758 --> 00:32:05,896
I know how you feel about it.

450
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:07,862
That's all right, Son.

451
00:32:07,965 --> 00:32:08,862
Goodbye, Mom.

452
00:32:08,965 --> 00:32:10,034
I'll write you every week.

453
00:32:10,137 --> 00:32:11,034
Don't you worry.

454
00:32:14,551 --> 00:32:16,379
Hilda.

455
00:32:16,482 --> 00:32:18,793
You

456
00:32:18,896 --> 00:32:22,379
[train bells]

457
00:32:24,862 --> 00:32:29,275
[dramatic music]

458
00:32:30,758 --> 00:32:32,448
[explosion]

459
00:32:32,551 --> 00:32:35,379
NARRATOR: 600,000causalities at [inaudible].

460
00:32:35,482 --> 00:32:38,275
A million dead and
wounded on the Sommes.

461
00:32:38,379 --> 00:32:42,758
And on the minds of men, therelentless pressure of war,

462
00:32:42,862 --> 00:32:44,620
dragging on into a third summer.

463
00:32:47,655 --> 00:32:50,482
[gunfire]

464
00:32:52,965 --> 00:32:56,206
At Jutland, in the
summer of 1916,

465
00:32:56,310 --> 00:32:59,172
the British Navy to
cover in the greatest

466
00:32:59,275 --> 00:33:02,793
sea battle of all time.

467
00:33:02,896 --> 00:33:06,344
[patriotic music]

468
00:33:17,172 --> 00:33:19,137
And for the first
time, Americans

469
00:33:19,241 --> 00:33:21,413
realized how great
was their dependence

470
00:33:21,517 --> 00:33:23,310
on the might of the Royal Navy.

471
00:33:26,620 --> 00:33:29,206
The whole thing boils
down to this, John.

472
00:33:29,310 --> 00:33:31,896
If we had a big army navy,we wouldn't have to worry

473
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:34,448
about getting into war.

474
00:33:34,551 --> 00:33:36,379
I'm afraid there are someof my fellow congressmen

475
00:33:36,482 --> 00:33:38,586
who will agree with, Jack.

476
00:33:38,689 --> 00:33:40,586
Well, they're wrong.

477
00:33:40,689 --> 00:33:43,241
And if congressmen won't dosomething about preparedness,

478
00:33:43,344 --> 00:33:44,586
we'll have to do it ourselves.

479
00:33:52,448 --> 00:33:56,344
Say, Dan, I want you to putsomething in your paper for me.

480
00:33:56,448 --> 00:33:57,827
What about?

481
00:33:57,931 --> 00:34:01,068
You know PlattsburghTraining Camp Teddy Roosevelt

482
00:34:01,172 --> 00:34:04,448
and General Woodruff started?

483
00:34:04,551 --> 00:34:06,931
I'm going to have one here.

484
00:34:07,034 --> 00:34:08,448
What for?

485
00:34:08,551 --> 00:34:10,103
There's a war
going on in Europe.

486
00:34:10,206 --> 00:34:13,103
You know as well as I do that ifFrance and England are licked,

487
00:34:13,206 --> 00:34:15,275
we're next.

488
00:34:15,379 --> 00:34:17,931
You've been a soldier
too long, Jack.

489
00:34:18,034 --> 00:34:20,413
Nobody's coming over
here to fight us.

490
00:34:20,517 --> 00:34:21,758
Maybe not.

491
00:34:21,862 --> 00:34:24,896
But suppose we have to goover there to fight them?

492
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:27,793
You know that's
not going to happen.

493
00:34:27,896 --> 00:34:31,206
[trumpets]

494
00:34:32,551 --> 00:34:35,620
NARRATOR: By 1916, WoodrowWilton now a candidate

495
00:34:35,724 --> 00:34:39,275
for reelection, could no longerignore the growing demand

496
00:34:39,379 --> 00:34:42,206
for national defense, andhe marched at the head

497
00:34:42,310 --> 00:34:45,344
of a Preparedness Parade.

498
00:34:45,448 --> 00:34:48,931
Republican candidate was SupremeCourt Justice Charles Evans

499
00:34:49,034 --> 00:34:53,620
Hughes, advocate of a strong andforthright US foreign policy.

500
00:34:57,862 --> 00:34:59,862
[chattering and cheering]

501
00:35:10,275 --> 00:35:12,379
That is the real
issue, the only

502
00:35:12,482 --> 00:35:17,068
real issue in this campaign.

503
00:35:17,172 --> 00:35:20,689
The President has
kept us out of war.

504
00:35:20,793 --> 00:35:24,206
[applause]

505
00:35:25,517 --> 00:35:29,448
He has sent notes to thewarring nations of Europe.

506
00:35:29,551 --> 00:35:32,448
That's all he has
done, is send notes.

507
00:35:32,551 --> 00:35:36,965
Yes, the President
has sent notes.

508
00:35:37,068 --> 00:35:42,689
But he has not sent one singleAmerican boy to his death

509
00:35:42,793 --> 00:35:44,655
on the battlefields.

510
00:35:44,758 --> 00:35:48,586
[applause]

511
00:35:51,655 --> 00:35:54,931
[parade music]

512
00:36:10,344 --> 00:36:11,689
11:10 PM.

513
00:36:11,793 --> 00:36:13,172
Madison, Wisconsin.

514
00:36:13,275 --> 00:36:18,724
Charles Evans Hughes has tiedWisconsin by large plurality.

515
00:36:18,827 --> 00:36:21,655
[cheering]

516
00:36:26,137 --> 00:36:27,344
11:15 PM.

517
00:36:27,448 --> 00:36:31,344
The Associated Press
reports that with five

518
00:36:31,448 --> 00:36:34,275
states still
unreported, Hughes is

519
00:36:34,379 --> 00:36:37,275
leading Wilson by a now margin.

520
00:36:37,379 --> 00:36:40,413
[cheering]

521
00:36:41,862 --> 00:36:44,000
[bell ringing]

522
00:36:46,827 --> 00:36:49,586
He's to a real President
of the United States,

523
00:36:49,689 --> 00:36:53,448
Charles Evans Hughes. [SINGING]Here's to Charlie Hughes,

524
00:36:53,551 --> 00:36:56,068
drink down, drink down.

525
00:36:56,172 --> 00:36:59,862
Here's to Charlie Hughes,drink her down, drink her down.

526
00:36:59,965 --> 00:37:04,241
Here's to Charlie Hughes, he'sin Woodrow Wilson's shoes.

527
00:37:04,344 --> 00:37:08,965
Drink her down, drink her down,drink her down, down, down.

528
00:37:19,793 --> 00:37:23,275
NARRATOR: With the campaignslogan "Kept Us Out of War,"

529
00:37:23,379 --> 00:37:24,655
Woodrow Wilton was re-elected.

530
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:35,448
[cheering]

531
00:37:42,344 --> 00:37:46,379
[explosions]

532
00:37:47,862 --> 00:37:50,758
The war in Europe had longsince become a merciless process

533
00:37:50,862 --> 00:37:52,068
of attrition.

534
00:37:52,172 --> 00:37:57,482
To break the stalemate, Britainhad introduced the tank.

535
00:37:57,586 --> 00:37:59,517
Germany was using liquid fire.

536
00:38:03,344 --> 00:38:06,517
The war went on,
into another winter,

537
00:38:06,620 --> 00:38:11,862
bringing death to some
5,000 men each day.

538
00:38:11,965 --> 00:38:15,275
[action music]

539
00:38:15,379 --> 00:38:18,827
[zooming]

540
00:38:28,137 --> 00:38:31,482
War had already touched theAmerican community in many ways

541
00:38:31,586 --> 00:38:33,965
by the summer of 1916.

542
00:38:34,068 --> 00:38:38,931
[ragtime music]

543
00:38:40,724 --> 00:38:44,379
The Lafayette Escadrilleis all Americans, isn't it?

544
00:38:44,482 --> 00:38:45,724
Yes, sir.

545
00:38:45,827 --> 00:38:46,724
Now, what would happen
to you if the United

546
00:38:46,827 --> 00:38:48,000
States should go into the war.

547
00:38:48,103 --> 00:38:50,000
Well, I understand
we'll be commissioned

548
00:38:50,103 --> 00:38:51,310
in the US Army flying corps.

549
00:38:51,413 --> 00:38:52,275
Hello, Hal.

550
00:38:52,379 --> 00:38:53,172
Hello, Mr. Meredith.

551
00:38:53,275 --> 00:38:54,758
It's good to see you.

552
00:38:54,862 --> 00:38:55,965
It's good to see you back againall in one piece, isn't it?

553
00:38:56,068 --> 00:38:56,793
Sure is.

554
00:38:56,896 --> 00:38:58,344
Certainly is.

555
00:38:58,448 --> 00:39:01,931
[ragtime music]

556
00:39:02,034 --> 00:39:03,862
Hiya, Hal.

557
00:39:03,965 --> 00:39:05,793
Hello, Betsy.

558
00:39:05,896 --> 00:39:06,896
How are you?

559
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:07,724
Swell.

560
00:39:10,551 --> 00:39:11,793
Boy, I guess the
last thing you ever

561
00:39:11,896 --> 00:39:14,103
thought when you graduatedwas that you'd be

562
00:39:14,206 --> 00:39:16,586
an aviator in the French army.

563
00:39:16,689 --> 00:39:20,517
Say how old do you have
to be to go to France?

564
00:39:20,620 --> 00:39:24,103
[ragtime music]

565
00:39:28,551 --> 00:39:30,448
Hello, Anna.

566
00:39:30,551 --> 00:39:33,034
How's the party?

567
00:39:33,137 --> 00:39:35,448
All right.

568
00:39:35,551 --> 00:39:39,413
What's the trouble, Anna?

569
00:39:39,517 --> 00:39:42,379
Mother got a
cablegram this morning.

570
00:39:42,482 --> 00:39:44,000
My father was killed.

571
00:39:47,241 --> 00:39:47,965
Anna.

572
00:39:51,206 --> 00:39:54,275
Do you think WalterAverill will be able to get

573
00:39:54,379 --> 00:39:55,862
back to America on his leave?

574
00:39:55,965 --> 00:39:56,896
I don't know.

575
00:39:57,000 --> 00:39:58,103
He's a sub-lieutenant
now, and they

576
00:39:58,206 --> 00:39:59,206
may not be able to spare him.

577
00:40:03,275 --> 00:40:06,724
[trumpeting]

578
00:40:14,793 --> 00:40:16,379
Colonel.

579
00:40:16,482 --> 00:40:17,206
Hut.

580
00:40:24,241 --> 00:40:26,034
Hut.

581
00:40:26,137 --> 00:40:26,896
[inaudible]

582
00:40:29,655 --> 00:40:31,413
Left shoulder.

583
00:40:31,517 --> 00:40:32,482
[inaudible]

584
00:40:35,310 --> 00:40:37,379
Right shoulder.

585
00:40:37,482 --> 00:40:39,172
[inaudible]

586
00:40:39,275 --> 00:40:40,000
[inaudible]

587
00:40:45,206 --> 00:40:45,965
[inaudible]

588
00:40:53,206 --> 00:40:55,000
Quiet in the rank.

589
00:40:55,103 --> 00:40:57,724
You men are at attention.

590
00:40:57,827 --> 00:41:00,448
And while I'm on thesubject, you might as well

591
00:41:00,551 --> 00:41:02,724
get it through your heads
right now but you're

592
00:41:02,827 --> 00:41:05,862
not out here for a vacation.

593
00:41:05,965 --> 00:41:09,172
You're here to learn
to do a job, the job

594
00:41:09,275 --> 00:41:12,241
of defending your country.

595
00:41:12,344 --> 00:41:16,068
Maybe it won't be very longbefore you have to do that job,

596
00:41:16,172 --> 00:41:17,275
and do it right.

597
00:41:17,379 --> 00:41:18,068
[inaudible]

598
00:41:21,448 --> 00:41:22,206
Dismissed.

599
00:41:30,655 --> 00:41:31,379
Hello, Dad.

600
00:41:31,482 --> 00:41:32,241
Hello, Ralph.

601
00:41:32,344 --> 00:41:34,620
Hello, Mom.

602
00:41:34,724 --> 00:41:36,965
Why, Ralph, you must
be tired to death.

603
00:41:37,068 --> 00:41:38,241
No, I'm fine.

604
00:41:38,344 --> 00:41:39,275
This is fun.

605
00:41:39,379 --> 00:41:40,344
Do they give you plenty to eat?

606
00:41:40,448 --> 00:41:41,206
Sure.

607
00:41:41,310 --> 00:41:42,310
All I can hold.

608
00:41:42,413 --> 00:41:43,310
Don't worry, Mom.

609
00:41:43,413 --> 00:41:45,379
Oh, Ralph, I can't help it.

610
00:41:45,482 --> 00:41:47,965
I hate to see you
in that uniform.

611
00:41:48,068 --> 00:41:49,241
I hate it all.

612
00:41:49,344 --> 00:41:51,413
Aw, Mom.

613
00:41:51,517 --> 00:41:53,655
Dad, you like it, don't you?

614
00:41:53,758 --> 00:41:54,793
You look fine, Ralph.

615
00:41:54,896 --> 00:41:56,000
Just fine.

616
00:41:56,103 --> 00:41:58,931
[cannon]

617
00:41:59,034 --> 00:42:02,310
[trumpeting]

618
00:42:17,896 --> 00:42:19,862
In Europe on a dozen
separate battle fronts

619
00:42:19,965 --> 00:42:23,310
by the winter of 1916,
4 million men had met

620
00:42:23,413 --> 00:42:27,931
death in ways new and dreadful.

621
00:42:28,034 --> 00:42:30,034
And Germany had introducedthe most terrible

622
00:42:30,137 --> 00:42:35,000
of all the First World War's newweapons-- poison gas, chlorine

623
00:42:35,103 --> 00:42:37,931
and [inaudible] to choke
the lungs and throat,

624
00:42:38,034 --> 00:42:41,482
mustard to burn
the eyes and skin.

625
00:42:41,586 --> 00:42:44,724
[dramatic music]

626
00:42:51,379 --> 00:42:54,379
The use of poison gas seemedhorrible and barbarous

627
00:42:54,482 --> 00:42:57,586
than any other single actionof the German high command.

628
00:42:57,689 --> 00:43:02,448
And Americans were fast
reaching a decision.

629
00:43:02,551 --> 00:43:06,655
[cheering]

630
00:43:21,896 --> 00:43:25,758
And has also received
the [inaudible]

631
00:43:25,862 --> 00:43:28,517
for bravery in action.

632
00:43:28,620 --> 00:43:30,655
Can you imagine that
guy, Hal Fisher?

633
00:43:30,758 --> 00:43:32,827
With his name all
over the paper?

634
00:43:32,931 --> 00:43:34,724
Boy, I guess I was born
just a little too late.

635
00:43:34,827 --> 00:43:36,413
Don't worry.

636
00:43:36,517 --> 00:43:38,034
We're going to get
our chance yet.

637
00:43:38,137 --> 00:43:41,655
Did I tell you I'm gettinginto the Naval Reserve?

638
00:43:41,758 --> 00:43:44,000
Naval Reserve.

639
00:43:44,103 --> 00:43:46,793
You oughta be in
the National Guard.

640
00:43:46,896 --> 00:43:50,068
I'll bet we go over, thefirst week, we're in the war.

641
00:43:50,172 --> 00:43:53,413
[patriotic music]

642
00:43:59,517 --> 00:44:02,448
[cheering]

643
00:44:13,379 --> 00:44:17,000
Anna, I think I'm going tosign up in the Marine Corps.

644
00:44:20,068 --> 00:44:22,896
Well, I want to do something.

645
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:24,068
We're going to be in this war.

646
00:44:26,827 --> 00:44:28,310
Fred, what will
your father say?

647
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:35,000
I don't know, but
I'm going to do it.

648
00:44:35,103 --> 00:44:39,000
[cheering]

649
00:44:49,275 --> 00:44:52,793
NARRATOR: By now, pacifist songswere finding a little favor.

650
00:44:52,896 --> 00:44:53,689
[music playing]

651
00:44:53,793 --> 00:44:54,965
SINGER: Hello, my dear.

652
00:44:55,068 --> 00:44:58,655
I heard a mother murmur
through her tears.

653
00:44:58,758 --> 00:45:05,103
I didn't raise my
boy to be a soldier.

654
00:45:05,206 --> 00:45:09,241
I brought him up to
be my pride and joy.

655
00:45:09,344 --> 00:45:10,551
Waiter.

656
00:45:10,655 --> 00:45:12,862
Waiter.

657
00:45:12,965 --> 00:45:14,413
What's the trouble, sir?

658
00:45:14,517 --> 00:45:15,275
How much is this?

659
00:45:18,448 --> 00:45:20,034
Why can't you make up
your mind whether you're

660
00:45:20,137 --> 00:45:22,517
Germans or Americans?

661
00:45:22,620 --> 00:45:24,068
Come on, let's get out of here.

662
00:45:26,586 --> 00:45:28,896
SINGER: It's time to put
the sword and gun away.

663
00:45:31,241 --> 00:45:37,068
There'd be no war today ifmothers all would say I didn't

664
00:45:37,172 --> 00:45:42,344
raise my boy to be a soldier.

665
00:45:42,448 --> 00:45:45,551
[applause]

666
00:45:47,000 --> 00:45:50,482
[dramatic music]

667
00:45:52,206 --> 00:45:56,000
[explosion]

668
00:45:59,310 --> 00:46:02,137
NARRATOR: Fires and explosionsof mysterious origin

669
00:46:02,241 --> 00:46:05,000
had plagued the nation'sindustrial regions for two

670
00:46:05,103 --> 00:46:07,310
years, and Americans
were now beginning

671
00:46:07,413 --> 00:46:10,586
to realize that these disasterswere not all accidents.

672
00:46:20,241 --> 00:46:20,965
Thank you.

673
00:46:29,310 --> 00:46:30,310
How do you, sir?

674
00:46:30,413 --> 00:46:33,448
How do you do,
Professor Bensinger?

675
00:46:33,551 --> 00:46:34,310
Am I disturbing you?

676
00:46:34,413 --> 00:46:35,379
Not at all.

677
00:46:35,482 --> 00:46:37,793
Is there something
I can do for you?

678
00:46:37,896 --> 00:46:39,896
If you could give
me a few minutes.

679
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:40,931
Certainly.

680
00:46:45,137 --> 00:46:48,310
[inaudible] the German embassy.

681
00:46:48,413 --> 00:46:49,896
Yes?

682
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:52,758
Professor Bensinger,
it is imperative

683
00:46:52,862 --> 00:46:55,689
we stop the shipment
of American munitions

684
00:46:55,793 --> 00:46:58,000
to France and England.

685
00:46:58,103 --> 00:47:02,482
As a German who is a respectedmember of this community,

686
00:47:02,586 --> 00:47:06,413
your influence can
help the fatherland.

687
00:47:06,517 --> 00:47:11,689
Herr [inaudible], my
home is now in America.

688
00:47:11,793 --> 00:47:15,827
I have a wife and twochildren who are Americans.

689
00:47:15,931 --> 00:47:19,896
If only for their sake,
I cannot take sides.

690
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:23,137
The war in Europe
is a terrible thing.

691
00:47:23,241 --> 00:47:25,448
Actually, I wish I
could do something

692
00:47:25,551 --> 00:47:27,413
to help the fatherland.

693
00:47:27,517 --> 00:47:30,655
But I must be clear
to you, I cannot.

694
00:47:33,448 --> 00:47:36,586
You know I must report
your answer to Germany,

695
00:47:36,689 --> 00:47:37,482
Professor Bensinger?

696
00:47:42,103 --> 00:47:44,068
NARRATOR: Many Americanswere beginning to suspect

697
00:47:44,172 --> 00:47:47,517
that the German ambassador,
Johann von Bernstroff

698
00:47:47,620 --> 00:47:51,034
was directing planned sabotageon a nationwide scale.

699
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:03,103
[explosion]

700
00:48:05,827 --> 00:48:09,862
An explosion of munitions onBlack Tom Island, New Jersey

701
00:48:09,965 --> 00:48:11,896
have rocked an area of 70 miles.

702
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:14,137
Another explosion at
Kingsland, New Jersey

703
00:48:14,241 --> 00:48:15,896
destroyed in a few minutesmillions of dollars

704
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:17,068
worth of shells and ammunition.

705
00:48:19,793 --> 00:48:22,827
Time and time again came
evidence and sabeteurs,

706
00:48:22,931 --> 00:48:25,172
well-organized
and financed, were

707
00:48:25,275 --> 00:48:27,724
attempting the
systematic destruction

708
00:48:27,827 --> 00:48:29,310
of US munition plants.

709
00:48:32,172 --> 00:48:36,551
The violence of war hadtouched the nation's shores.

710
00:48:36,655 --> 00:48:39,655
And America's traditional
sense of security

711
00:48:39,758 --> 00:48:43,482
was shaken to the core.

712
00:48:43,586 --> 00:48:50,172
By 1917, Americans were
facing the inevitable.

713
00:48:50,275 --> 00:48:54,655
I think most Americans feelabout the way I do, John.

714
00:48:54,758 --> 00:48:57,724
You know I've never
believed the propaganda.

715
00:48:57,827 --> 00:49:04,275
I've never been frightenedby spies, and I've hated war.

716
00:49:04,379 --> 00:49:06,068
But the time has
come when we've got

717
00:49:06,172 --> 00:49:09,275
to fight for the decent,civilized things in life.

718
00:49:12,448 --> 00:49:16,689
It's just that I hate to thinkthat I'll ever have to vote

719
00:49:16,793 --> 00:49:18,586
to put this country into war.

720
00:49:18,689 --> 00:49:21,275
NARRATOR: More and more, the warin Europe coming into the homes

721
00:49:21,379 --> 00:49:22,965
of the American community.

722
00:49:23,068 --> 00:49:26,275
Mind the office for
awhile, will you, Eddie?

723
00:49:26,379 --> 00:49:29,206
I've gotta deliver a
message across town.

724
00:49:29,310 --> 00:49:31,517
Can't I deliver it for you?

725
00:49:31,620 --> 00:49:33,275
I think I'd better
deliver this one myself.

726
00:49:37,068 --> 00:49:41,137
[typing]

727
00:49:47,655 --> 00:49:50,758
Gee, Walter Averill.

728
00:49:58,448 --> 00:49:59,724
We'll run this one, George.

729
00:50:03,172 --> 00:50:06,551
[choral music]

730
00:50:38,758 --> 00:50:43,137
The death of Walter Averillseems to have brought

731
00:50:43,241 --> 00:50:47,206
the war in Europe very close.

732
00:50:47,310 --> 00:50:49,655
Perhaps this war is
no concern of ours.

733
00:50:52,413 --> 00:50:55,413
Perhaps we should be in it.

734
00:50:55,517 --> 00:50:59,482
There are sincere thinkingmen and women on both sides.

735
00:50:59,586 --> 00:51:03,724
And we are under terrifyingpressure on this question.

736
00:51:06,620 --> 00:51:09,413
From England and
France and Germany

737
00:51:09,517 --> 00:51:13,862
come all kinds of reports.

738
00:51:13,965 --> 00:51:17,241
Most of them are half truths.

739
00:51:17,344 --> 00:51:19,482
Some of them are lies.

740
00:51:19,586 --> 00:51:22,931
But Walter Averill didn'tgo to France for lies.

741
00:51:23,034 --> 00:51:25,413
He didn't go because
of the lurid tales

742
00:51:25,517 --> 00:51:30,000
about the Hun and [inaudible].

743
00:51:30,103 --> 00:51:32,827
I think Walter
believed in his heart

744
00:51:32,931 --> 00:51:36,862
the same as I believe
in mine that there is

745
00:51:36,965 --> 00:51:43,137
a basic democratic principleand a primitive might

746
00:51:43,241 --> 00:51:46,241
makes right instinct.

747
00:51:46,344 --> 00:51:51,655
And today, these
two are fighting

748
00:51:51,758 --> 00:51:54,620
to see which will survive.

749
00:51:54,724 --> 00:51:58,931
I think that's the fight forwhich young Walter Averill was

750
00:51:59,034 --> 00:52:00,448
willing to give up his life.

751
00:52:11,793 --> 00:52:14,000
NARRATOR: Like an openchallenge to the United States

752
00:52:14,103 --> 00:52:18,413
in the first weeks of 1917 cameGermany's declaration that she

753
00:52:18,517 --> 00:52:21,034
was resuming
unrestricted warfare

754
00:52:21,137 --> 00:52:23,413
against the vessels
of all nations,

755
00:52:23,517 --> 00:52:24,931
belligerent and neutral.

756
00:52:29,068 --> 00:52:31,000
Now the German
government tells us

757
00:52:31,103 --> 00:52:33,517
that she will let us
send just one ship

758
00:52:33,620 --> 00:52:37,068
a week across the Atlantic.

759
00:52:37,172 --> 00:52:44,482
We are told when it must leave,when it must arrive, and where.

760
00:52:44,586 --> 00:52:47,482
We are told to
paint stripes on it.

761
00:52:47,586 --> 00:52:50,379
That it must fly a flag
of red and white checks

762
00:52:50,482 --> 00:52:53,448
like a farmer's table cloth.

763
00:52:53,551 --> 00:52:58,344
I think I can truthfully saythat no man in this house

764
00:52:58,448 --> 00:53:02,827
has advocated caution
more consistently,

765
00:53:02,931 --> 00:53:05,965
has more consistently
championed the cause

766
00:53:06,068 --> 00:53:08,793
of neutrality and peace.

767
00:53:08,896 --> 00:53:13,517
Now, it seems that the effortsof all of us may be in vain.

768
00:53:16,000 --> 00:53:20,620
If they are to be in
vain, then I say this.

769
00:53:20,724 --> 00:53:24,344
Let us thank God that
we are on the side

770
00:53:24,448 --> 00:53:26,793
of justice and the right.

771
00:53:30,034 --> 00:53:33,931
NARRATOR: [inaudible] came USAmbassador James W. Gerard,

772
00:53:34,034 --> 00:53:36,551
and his disturbing rumorsthat Germans were attempting

773
00:53:36,655 --> 00:53:39,068
to promote an attack
through Mexico

774
00:53:39,172 --> 00:53:42,103
against the United States.

775
00:53:42,206 --> 00:53:45,000
[band music]

776
00:53:49,379 --> 00:53:51,931
The nation was tense
with expectation.

777
00:53:52,034 --> 00:53:54,517
But on the cold March
day of Woodrow Wilson's

778
00:53:54,620 --> 00:53:57,965
second inaugural, the
nation's men of state,

779
00:53:58,068 --> 00:53:59,758
as well as all the solemnthousands who crowded

780
00:53:59,862 --> 00:54:02,310
into Washington, feltthat they were witnessing

781
00:54:02,413 --> 00:54:04,551
the close of one era
in American history,

782
00:54:04,655 --> 00:54:08,103
the beginning of another.

783
00:54:08,206 --> 00:54:12,689
[band playing]

784
00:54:25,931 --> 00:54:29,724
By March, the US flag
had been all but driven

785
00:54:29,827 --> 00:54:31,965
from the Atlantic
by German submarine.

786
00:54:32,068 --> 00:54:36,896
For America, freedom of theseas had ceased to exist.

787
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:39,758
As the first important
act of his second term,

788
00:54:39,862 --> 00:54:42,482
Woodrow Wilson signed
an executive order

789
00:54:42,586 --> 00:54:46,655
which armed all US merchantships with naval guns.

790
00:54:46,758 --> 00:54:50,137
It was another compromise,called by Woodrow

791
00:54:50,241 --> 00:54:51,931
Wilson armed neutrality.

792
00:55:07,586 --> 00:55:09,068
Congressman [inaudible]?

793
00:55:09,172 --> 00:55:09,965
Good evening.

794
00:55:10,068 --> 00:55:11,827
This is Western Union.

795
00:55:11,931 --> 00:55:14,172
I have a telegram for
you from Washington

796
00:55:14,275 --> 00:55:16,344
signed Carter, Sergeant at arms.

797
00:55:16,448 --> 00:55:21,310
The message reads, three
more American ships,

798
00:55:21,413 --> 00:55:24,586
having been torpedoed,
the President

799
00:55:24,689 --> 00:55:29,034
has advanced the date of aspecial session of Congress

800
00:55:29,137 --> 00:55:31,586
through April 2.

801
00:55:31,689 --> 00:55:35,793
That's signed Carter,
Sergeant at Arms.

802
00:55:35,896 --> 00:55:39,068
NARRATOR: Armed
neutrality had failed.

803
00:55:39,172 --> 00:55:42,862
The American peoplelooked to the White House.

804
00:55:42,965 --> 00:55:46,758
For three years, Woodrow Wiltonhad compromised with Germany.

805
00:55:46,862 --> 00:55:50,689
And each new compromisehad brought new indignity.

806
00:55:50,793 --> 00:55:52,896
Now, his people wanted war.

807
00:55:58,172 --> 00:56:03,689
On the evening of April2, 1917, the entire nation

808
00:56:03,793 --> 00:56:06,034
awaited Woodrow
Wilson's fateful answer.

809
00:56:10,137 --> 00:56:12,586
[trumpets]

810
00:56:14,103 --> 00:56:15,689
The answer came.

811
00:56:15,793 --> 00:56:18,103
Calling upon the nationto mobilize its resources

812
00:56:18,206 --> 00:56:22,241
and its manpower, WoodrowWilton declared that America had

813
00:56:22,344 --> 00:56:24,448
no quarrel with
the German people,

814
00:56:24,551 --> 00:56:27,827
sought no dominion,
and no conquest.

815
00:56:27,931 --> 00:56:30,379
But the Imperial
German government

816
00:56:30,482 --> 00:56:33,724
had subjected the rights andthe ideals of the United States

817
00:56:33,827 --> 00:56:37,724
to such violation as no nationof free men could endure.

818
00:56:40,551 --> 00:56:41,862
It's a great speech so far.

819
00:56:46,103 --> 00:56:49,275
Here's the end of it now.

820
00:56:49,379 --> 00:56:52,793
[typing]

821
00:56:57,965 --> 00:57:03,241
For democracy, for
the right of those

822
00:57:03,344 --> 00:57:12,068
who submit to authority to havea voice in their government.

823
00:57:12,172 --> 00:57:17,000
For the rights andliberties of small nations.

824
00:57:17,103 --> 00:57:23,448
For a universal dominionof right by such a concert

825
00:57:23,551 --> 00:57:28,586
of free peoples as
shall bring peace

826
00:57:28,689 --> 00:57:34,689
and safety to all nations,and make the world

827
00:57:34,793 --> 00:57:39,965
itself at last free.

828
00:57:40,068 --> 00:57:49,137
To such a task, we can dedicateour lives and our fortune

829
00:57:49,241 --> 00:57:54,827
with the pride of those whoknow that the day has come when

830
00:57:54,931 --> 00:58:03,000
America is privileged to spendher blood for the principles

831
00:58:03,103 --> 00:58:07,965
which gave her
birth, and happiness,

832
00:58:08,068 --> 00:58:14,413
and the peace which
she has treasured.

833
00:58:14,517 --> 00:58:20,310
God helping her,
she can do no other.

834
00:58:27,724 --> 00:58:30,551
OK, George.

835
00:58:30,655 --> 00:58:32,379
Three column box
on the front page.

836
00:58:32,482 --> 00:58:33,965
Run it over.

837
00:58:34,068 --> 00:58:39,758
Head it "The President's WarMessage," with a main head,

838
00:58:39,862 --> 00:58:45,896
"Wilson Calls For War."

839
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:49,172
[bells]

840
00:58:54,241 --> 00:58:58,724
[whooshing noises]

841
00:59:23,586 --> 00:59:27,034
[band music]

842
00:59:27,724 --> 00:59:28,655
Aye, aye, sir.

843
00:59:36,206 --> 00:59:37,172
Date of birth?

844
00:59:37,275 --> 00:59:41,413
February 10, 1899.

845
00:59:41,517 --> 00:59:42,517
Place of birth?

846
00:59:42,620 --> 00:59:45,000
Miles City, Montana.

847
00:59:45,103 --> 00:59:49,344
[cheering]

848
01:00:04,827 --> 01:00:09,793
Boys, I'm not going tomake a speech here today.

849
01:00:09,896 --> 01:00:14,344
You're leaving home to begin
the long trek to France.

850
01:00:14,448 --> 01:00:19,137
No words of mine can tell youwhat you're going to fight for.

851
01:00:19,241 --> 01:00:19,965
You all know.

852
01:00:24,827 --> 01:00:30,655
The only thing I can sayis we're all proud of you.

853
01:00:30,758 --> 01:00:35,448
Good bye, and good luck.

854
01:00:35,551 --> 01:00:38,724
[military commands]

855
01:00:44,586 --> 01:00:48,655
[patriotic music]

856
01:00:54,517 --> 01:00:58,379
[cheering]

857
01:01:37,413 --> 01:01:41,000
[train whistle]

858
01:01:41,793 --> 01:01:46,137
[cheering]

859
01:02:12,379 --> 01:02:15,241
NARRATOR: With serious
purpose, the nation

860
01:02:15,344 --> 01:02:18,965
dug in for the biggest
job it had ever tackled.

861
01:02:19,068 --> 01:02:23,241
Starting with a regulararmy of 130,000 and 70,000

862
01:02:23,344 --> 01:02:26,310
half-trained,
ill-equipped reserves,

863
01:02:26,413 --> 01:02:28,206
the United States
undertook a mobilization

864
01:02:28,310 --> 01:02:31,413
of manpower and resourceswithout precedent

865
01:02:31,517 --> 01:02:34,344
in any age or any time.

866
01:02:34,448 --> 01:02:40,482
To equip America's soldierswas US industry's first job.

867
01:02:40,586 --> 01:02:45,586
Production began on 14 millionuniforms, 27 million pairs

868
01:02:45,689 --> 01:02:54,103
of shoes, 3 and 1/2 millionrifles and bayonets, a quarter

869
01:02:54,206 --> 01:02:55,172
of a million machine guns.

870
01:02:59,275 --> 01:03:02,034
[band music]

871
01:03:02,137 --> 01:03:05,034
In the nation's war
effort, every citizen

872
01:03:05,137 --> 01:03:07,000
was to take a part.

873
01:03:07,103 --> 01:03:08,724
Ed, how about
putting me to work

874
01:03:08,827 --> 01:03:12,620
as one of your four minute men.

875
01:03:12,724 --> 01:03:14,758
You young fellows havemore than you can handle.

876
01:03:14,862 --> 01:03:18,931
And I'd like to help
in this war too.

877
01:03:19,034 --> 01:03:20,655
Well, Dr. Hatfield,
it's pretty strenuous.

878
01:03:20,758 --> 01:03:22,551
Four or five speeches a day.

879
01:03:22,655 --> 01:03:24,448
That doesn't worry me a bit.

880
01:03:24,551 --> 01:03:26,551
I've been preaching
sermons since you

881
01:03:26,655 --> 01:03:28,862
were a boy in knee pants.

882
01:03:28,965 --> 01:03:29,793
All right.

883
01:03:29,896 --> 01:03:30,620
When can you start?

884
01:03:30,724 --> 01:03:33,034
Start now.

885
01:03:33,137 --> 01:03:36,620
[patriotic music]

886
01:03:40,137 --> 01:03:43,724
NARRATOR: Through liberty loans,the American people raised

887
01:03:43,827 --> 01:03:47,275
the huge sum of $24 billion.

888
01:03:47,379 --> 01:03:50,586
[cheering]

889
01:03:59,379 --> 01:04:01,758
Within three months afterthe declaration of war

890
01:04:01,862 --> 01:04:06,000
came the draft, the firstmilitary conscription since

891
01:04:06,103 --> 01:04:08,241
the war between the states.

892
01:04:08,344 --> 01:04:11,827
24 million men of militaryage registered for war service

893
01:04:11,931 --> 01:04:15,172
and waited for their
numbers to come up.

894
01:04:15,275 --> 01:04:19,103
In the 19 months of war,
there were to be three

895
01:04:19,206 --> 01:04:20,275
drawings of the draft lottery.

896
01:04:23,172 --> 01:04:24,655
Is that you, stranger?

897
01:04:24,758 --> 01:04:25,793
Yup.

898
01:04:25,896 --> 01:04:29,000
I had a hunch my
number was due up.

899
01:04:29,103 --> 01:04:30,965
Look, there's another one.

900
01:04:31,068 --> 01:04:33,965
NARRATOR: By the spring
of 1918, a nation

901
01:04:34,068 --> 01:04:36,344
that for half a centuryhad not fought a major war

902
01:04:36,448 --> 01:04:39,379
had called nearly 3 millionof its citizens to the colors.

903
01:04:42,482 --> 01:04:46,000
[parade music]

904
01:04:54,931 --> 01:04:58,896
Another 3 million men wereat work in US war industries.

905
01:04:59,000 --> 01:05:02,862
The biggest job was
steel, and more steel.

906
01:05:02,965 --> 01:05:05,724
Steel for big shell.

907
01:05:05,827 --> 01:05:08,172
More steel for the big guns.

908
01:05:08,275 --> 01:05:11,793
With its experience in supplyingFrench and British armies,

909
01:05:11,896 --> 01:05:13,965
American industry
in the first year

910
01:05:14,068 --> 01:05:18,379
produced 1 million
tons of munition.

911
01:05:18,482 --> 01:05:22,793
Meanwhile, in France, Frenchand British manpower continued

912
01:05:22,896 --> 01:05:25,689
to hold off the
powerful war machine,

913
01:05:25,793 --> 01:05:31,344
for their new ally 3,000 milesaway was unprepared, and could

914
01:05:31,448 --> 01:05:33,000
not send the trained
men so desperately

915
01:05:33,103 --> 01:05:42,517
needed to stop the greatGerman drive of late 1917.

916
01:05:42,620 --> 01:05:46,310
It was not until early 1918that America's first million

917
01:05:46,413 --> 01:05:49,103
were equipped and in training.

918
01:05:49,206 --> 01:05:52,793
Still ahead were weeks of
body-hardening marches,

919
01:05:52,896 --> 01:05:56,172
long, precious weeks oftraining for trench warfare,

920
01:05:56,275 --> 01:05:57,344
for going over the top.

921
01:06:23,034 --> 01:06:26,586
Crews for convoys
and submarine patrol.

922
01:06:26,689 --> 01:06:28,827
Crews for transports.

923
01:06:28,931 --> 01:06:32,551
Transferred to the Army were theNavy's regiments of US Marines,

924
01:06:32,655 --> 01:06:35,172
soldier/sailors who were
to take their places

925
01:06:35,275 --> 01:06:36,620
on the battlefields of France.

926
01:06:39,724 --> 01:06:42,482
MAN: Private Bensinger,report to commanding officer

927
01:06:42,586 --> 01:06:43,241
immediately.

928
01:06:43,344 --> 01:06:45,275
[inaudible], up front.

929
01:06:45,379 --> 01:06:51,931
Inspection, halt. [inaudible].

930
01:06:52,034 --> 01:06:54,896
Private Bensinger, sir.

931
01:06:55,000 --> 01:06:56,310
Yes, at ease.

932
01:06:59,034 --> 01:07:01,896
You know, I suppose
that your father's

933
01:07:02,000 --> 01:07:04,103
interned as an enemy alien.

934
01:07:04,206 --> 01:07:05,896
Yes, sir.

935
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:09,310
I'm sorry, but I have totell you that it will not

936
01:07:09,413 --> 01:07:11,724
be possible for you to gooverseas with the regiment

937
01:07:11,827 --> 01:07:13,965
under the circumstances.

938
01:07:14,068 --> 01:07:15,724
Yes, sir.

939
01:07:15,827 --> 01:07:18,000
That's all, I'm afraid.

940
01:07:18,103 --> 01:07:20,000
Aye, aye, sir.

941
01:07:20,103 --> 01:07:20,896
[singing]

942
01:07:21,000 --> 01:07:22,448
Good bye, Ma.

943
01:07:22,551 --> 01:07:24,137
Good bye, Pa.

944
01:07:24,241 --> 01:07:27,172
Goodbye, mule, with
your old hee-haw.

945
01:07:27,275 --> 01:07:29,689
I may not know what
the war's about,

946
01:07:29,793 --> 01:07:33,689
but I bet, by grass,
I'll soon find out.

947
01:07:33,793 --> 01:07:36,965
And oh, my sweetheart,
don't you fear.

948
01:07:37,068 --> 01:07:40,344
I'll bring you a
king for a souvenir.

949
01:07:40,448 --> 01:07:44,275
I'll get you a Turk
and Kaiser too.

950
01:07:44,379 --> 01:07:46,758
And that's about all
one fellow can do.

951
01:07:51,034 --> 01:07:53,068
Fellows getting
everything you wanted?

952
01:07:53,172 --> 01:07:55,827
Well, almost.

953
01:07:55,931 --> 01:07:57,034
That's fine.

954
01:07:57,137 --> 01:08:00,000
Nothings to good for our boys.

955
01:08:00,103 --> 01:08:02,862
[singing]

956
01:08:04,310 --> 01:08:05,965
Can I have a package
of Sweet Caps please?

957
01:08:06,068 --> 01:08:08,000
Why, certainly, Eddie.

958
01:08:08,103 --> 01:08:12,137
Did you know my outfit wasleaving tonight, Mrs. Averill?

959
01:08:12,241 --> 01:08:14,620
I suppose you're awfully glad.

960
01:08:14,724 --> 01:08:17,103
You bet.

961
01:08:17,206 --> 01:08:18,137
Well, hello there.

962
01:08:18,241 --> 01:08:19,137
Hello, dear.

963
01:08:19,241 --> 01:08:20,551
Evening, Ruth.

964
01:08:20,655 --> 01:08:25,896
I'll be with you
in just a minute

965
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:28,620
[singing]

966
01:08:30,931 --> 01:08:32,620
Mr. Lawton?

967
01:08:32,724 --> 01:08:33,551
Yes, my boy?

968
01:08:33,655 --> 01:08:35,310
Could you do me
a special favor?

969
01:08:35,413 --> 01:08:38,241
Doing favors is a
Congressman's main job.

970
01:08:38,344 --> 01:08:40,275
Well, do you supposeyou could have me ordered

971
01:08:40,379 --> 01:08:43,586
over to France in a hurry?

972
01:08:43,689 --> 01:08:45,689
I'm afraid if I don't get
over there pretty soon,

973
01:08:45,793 --> 01:08:47,793
there won't be any
war left to fight.

974
01:08:47,896 --> 01:08:52,137
--[laughing] I wouldn't worrytoo much about that, my boy.

975
01:08:52,241 --> 01:08:54,034
Good night, Mrs. Averill.

976
01:08:54,137 --> 01:08:56,896
Goodbye, Eddie.

977
01:08:57,000 --> 01:08:58,103
Good luck.

978
01:08:58,206 --> 01:08:59,931
Thank you.

979
01:09:00,034 --> 01:09:09,137
[singing]

980
01:09:09,241 --> 01:09:13,517
[patriotic music]

981
01:09:13,620 --> 01:09:16,931
NARRATOR: Under the commandof Admiral William Sims,

982
01:09:17,034 --> 01:09:19,103
since the declaration
of war, US destroyers

983
01:09:19,206 --> 01:09:22,482
had been helping to rid theseas of the German U-boat,

984
01:09:22,586 --> 01:09:27,655
with the aid of a new Britishweapon, the depth bomb.

985
01:09:27,758 --> 01:09:30,965
[patriotic music]

986
01:09:33,034 --> 01:09:35,862
[explosion]

987
01:09:38,724 --> 01:09:41,827
For a year, US dreadnaughtshad been with the British fleet

988
01:09:41,931 --> 01:09:42,793
at Scapa Flow.

989
01:09:48,862 --> 01:09:53,517
Now, the efforts of a unitedAmerica were producing results.

990
01:09:53,620 --> 01:09:56,379
1 million, trained
and equipped, were

991
01:09:56,482 --> 01:10:00,103
ready to join their Allies.

992
01:10:00,206 --> 01:10:03,655
[cheering]

993
01:10:06,965 --> 01:10:11,379
In May 1918 began thegreatest overseas movement

994
01:10:11,482 --> 01:10:14,172
of troops in all history.

995
01:10:14,275 --> 01:10:19,344
It was the citizen army of theworld's greatest democracy,

996
01:10:19,448 --> 01:10:22,344
to fight in a foreignland for American ideals.

997
01:10:22,448 --> 01:10:25,724
For those ideals,
one man in every 20

998
01:10:25,827 --> 01:10:28,482
was destined to
give up his life.

999
01:10:35,379 --> 01:10:40,827
[music playing]

1000
01:11:10,827 --> 01:11:14,310
[chattering]

1001
01:11:23,172 --> 01:11:25,482
To the war-weary
people of Europe,

1002
01:11:25,586 --> 01:11:29,137
these fresh and determinedmen were like saviors.

1003
01:11:29,241 --> 01:11:32,724
They had come none to soon.

1004
01:11:32,827 --> 01:11:37,068
[dramatic music]

1005
01:11:46,965 --> 01:11:52,000
In the spring of 1918,Germany had launched her last

1006
01:11:52,103 --> 01:11:53,379
and greatest offensive.

1007
01:11:53,482 --> 01:11:55,206
The first contingent
of Americans

1008
01:11:55,310 --> 01:12:00,379
met their baptism of fire in theheaviest fighting of the war.

1009
01:12:00,482 --> 01:12:02,965
[explosions]

1010
01:12:19,793 --> 01:12:22,034
Carrying on at home,
men, women, and children

1011
01:12:22,137 --> 01:12:25,793
were doing their bit,united toward a common goal.

1012
01:12:32,620 --> 01:12:34,862
Look, Miss [inaudible].

1013
01:12:34,965 --> 01:12:36,241
15 radishes.

1014
01:12:36,344 --> 01:12:38,965
Have gone over the top?

1015
01:12:39,068 --> 01:12:42,758
NARRATOR: In one single mammotheffort to help feed the Allied

1016
01:12:42,862 --> 01:12:46,620
armies, to keep aliveEurope's 30 million refugees,

1017
01:12:46,724 --> 01:12:49,379
the American peopleresolved that no sacrifice

1018
01:12:49,482 --> 01:12:53,931
could be too great, for
food would win the war.

1019
01:12:56,862 --> 01:13:00,172
To keep the endless convoysmoving with their cargoes

1020
01:13:00,275 --> 01:13:05,103
of food and materials of war,to replace the thousands of tons

1021
01:13:05,206 --> 01:13:06,965
of shipping destroyed
by German submarines,

1022
01:13:07,068 --> 01:13:08,793
American ship
builders were engaged

1023
01:13:08,896 --> 01:13:10,965
in the greatest constructionprogram of all time.

1024
01:13:13,896 --> 01:13:18,172
By the summer of 1918,
more than a ship a day

1025
01:13:18,275 --> 01:13:21,172
was going down the waves.

1026
01:13:21,275 --> 01:13:26,931
Ships of steal, wooden ships,even ships made of concrete.

1027
01:13:42,206 --> 01:13:47,310
To France in 1918 wentmany a US political figure,

1028
01:13:47,413 --> 01:13:49,862
great and small.

1029
01:13:49,965 --> 01:13:52,931
What is the type of
your artillery support?

1030
01:13:53,034 --> 01:14:00,586
[non-english speech]

1031
01:14:00,689 --> 01:14:05,137
We have in support bothheavy artillery and 75's.

1032
01:14:05,241 --> 01:14:06,482
Thank you.

1033
01:14:06,586 --> 01:14:09,620
NARRATOR: On French soil
in the ranks of the AEF,

1034
01:14:09,724 --> 01:14:12,931
2 million strong, were
many young Americans

1035
01:14:13,034 --> 01:14:15,068
destined to be among theirnation's future leaders.

1036
01:14:21,551 --> 01:14:24,862
And to the front
lines went Franklin

1037
01:14:24,965 --> 01:14:27,103
Delano Roosevelt, then
the young assistance

1038
01:14:27,206 --> 01:14:28,000
secretary of the Navy.

1039
01:14:43,862 --> 01:14:47,413
Courageous to the point ofrecklessness, American forces

1040
01:14:47,517 --> 01:14:53,310
by the fall of 1918 had sufferednearly 300,000 casualties,

1041
01:14:53,413 --> 01:14:55,931
50,000 killed in action.

1042
01:14:56,034 --> 01:14:56,724
Eddie?

1043
01:14:56,827 --> 01:15:00,689
Here's a friend of yours.

1044
01:15:00,793 --> 01:15:04,103
It's Sean Lawton
from back home, Eddie.

1045
01:15:04,206 --> 01:15:06,655
Mr. Lawton?

1046
01:15:06,758 --> 01:15:09,551
How did you ever find outwhere I was, Mr. Lawton.

1047
01:15:09,655 --> 01:15:11,793
Oh, that wasn't so hard.

1048
01:15:11,896 --> 01:15:14,620
Gee, I never expected
to see anybody

1049
01:15:14,724 --> 01:15:16,344
from back home way over here.

1050
01:15:20,896 --> 01:15:23,724
NARRATOR: There were
to be more casualties.

1051
01:15:23,827 --> 01:15:26,379
But in the Argonne
on September 29,

1052
01:15:26,482 --> 01:15:29,068
Americans had broken
Hindenburg Line,

1053
01:15:29,172 --> 01:15:33,413
last strong-hold of Germanforces on French soil.

1054
01:15:33,517 --> 01:15:35,206
Through the first
week of November,

1055
01:15:35,310 --> 01:15:38,310
there were repeated rumorsof German capitulation.

1056
01:15:38,413 --> 01:15:42,103
A false report reachedAmerica that an armistice

1057
01:15:42,206 --> 01:15:43,034
had been signed.

1058
01:15:43,137 --> 01:15:44,931
But the war went on.

1059
01:15:45,034 --> 01:15:47,862
[explosions]

1060
01:15:50,689 --> 01:15:54,344
Then, on November 11, 1918--

1061
01:15:54,448 --> 01:15:56,310
Hey!

1062
01:15:56,413 --> 01:15:58,896
MEN: Yay!

1063
01:15:59,000 --> 01:16:02,344
[cheering]

1064
01:16:24,000 --> 01:16:24,517
Hooray!

1065
01:16:24,620 --> 01:16:25,724
The war's over.

1066
01:16:34,103 --> 01:16:38,275
[cheering]

1067
01:17:11,068 --> 01:17:13,310
NARRATOR: It had come withbreathtaking suddenness.

1068
01:17:13,413 --> 01:17:17,034
No event in all recorded historyhad swept the minds and hearts

1069
01:17:17,137 --> 01:17:20,310
of men throughout theworld, with so deep and wild

1070
01:17:20,413 --> 01:17:23,241
a fervour of thanksgiving.

1071
01:17:23,344 --> 01:17:26,793
[singing]

1072
01:17:29,758 --> 01:17:31,620
[applause]

1073
01:17:31,724 --> 01:17:34,586
[cheering]

1074
01:17:34,689 --> 01:17:36,172
[non-english]

1075
01:17:36,275 --> 01:17:37,551
Vive la France!

1076
01:17:37,655 --> 01:17:39,517
Vive le President Wilson.

1077
01:17:39,620 --> 01:17:43,862
[cheering]

1078
01:17:43,965 --> 01:17:48,137
[patriotic music]

1079
01:17:58,655 --> 01:18:01,896
NARRATOR: It had taken fourlong years, from the combined

1080
01:18:02,000 --> 01:18:04,137
efforts of most of the
nations of the world,

1081
01:18:04,241 --> 01:18:06,724
to destroy the great Germanwar machine which had

1082
01:18:06,827 --> 01:18:07,931
threatened their civilization.

1083
01:18:15,068 --> 01:18:19,517
[music - "the first noel"]

1084
01:18:25,965 --> 01:18:28,793
The American community
in the winter of 1918

1085
01:18:28,896 --> 01:18:33,586
was preparing to
celebrate a new year.

1086
01:18:33,689 --> 01:18:37,034
Americans faced their futurewith the confidence of a people

1087
01:18:37,137 --> 01:18:39,551
who had accepted the
gravest responsibility

1088
01:18:39,655 --> 01:18:41,413
their age could offer.

1089
01:18:41,517 --> 01:18:45,000
They had fought for andpreserved the way of life which

1090
01:18:45,103 --> 01:18:46,793
was their American heritage.

1091
01:18:53,896 --> 01:18:58,448
In a few minutes
now, it'll be 1919.

1092
01:18:58,551 --> 01:18:59,275
Dan, how about a toast?

1093
01:19:02,655 --> 01:19:05,758
You know, I have
never forgotten,

1094
01:19:05,862 --> 01:19:08,758
and I suppose I
never will forget,

1095
01:19:08,862 --> 01:19:11,068
the President's
words when he told

1096
01:19:11,172 --> 01:19:15,103
us why we were going to war.

1097
01:19:15,206 --> 01:19:24,137
I would say, to the things wefought for and won-- democracy,

1098
01:19:24,241 --> 01:19:28,034
the rights of those whosubmit to authority to have

1099
01:19:28,137 --> 01:19:33,000
a voice in their own government,
the rights and liberties

1100
01:19:33,103 --> 01:19:36,551
of small nations,
a peace that will

1101
01:19:36,655 --> 01:19:41,448
bring safety to allpeoples, and make the world

1102
01:19:41,551 --> 01:19:46,827
itself at last free.

1103
01:19:46,931 --> 01:19:51,965
[trumpets]

1104
01:20:23,586 --> 01:20:27,310
[explosions]

1105
01:20:27,413 --> 01:20:29,379
NARRATOR: Guiding
the Germany of 1940

1106
01:20:29,482 --> 01:20:31,827
and its war machine
is a blueprint

1107
01:20:31,931 --> 01:20:37,068
for world conquest, a book whichevery good Nazi knows by heart.

1108
01:20:37,172 --> 01:20:39,586
Its title? "Mein Kampf."

1109
01:20:39,689 --> 01:20:40,413
Its author?

1110
01:20:40,517 --> 01:20:42,068
Adolf Hitler.

1111
01:20:42,172 --> 01:20:47,965
"Democracy is a monstrosity,born of filth and fire.

1112
01:20:48,068 --> 01:20:52,379
While democracy talks, we act.

1113
01:20:52,482 --> 01:20:58,862
Borders are made by man,and can be changed by man.

1114
01:20:58,965 --> 01:21:05,034
Germany will be the
world power or nothing.

1115
01:21:05,137 --> 01:21:12,137
Almighty God,
bless our battles."

1116
01:21:12,241 --> 01:21:15,448
First step to conquest
in the Nazi scheme

1117
01:21:15,551 --> 01:21:19,965
is to demoralize the enemy bypropaganda, to inspire fear,

1118
01:21:20,068 --> 01:21:22,586
and to breed terror.

1119
01:21:22,689 --> 01:21:26,103
At Bermuda, Britishcontraband control officers

1120
01:21:26,206 --> 01:21:29,448
had intercepted tons ofNazi propaganda, destined

1121
01:21:29,551 --> 01:21:31,655
to make the Americas
fear the might

1122
01:21:31,758 --> 01:21:34,586
of Germany's great war machine.

1123
01:21:34,689 --> 01:21:38,758
Most famous piece of confiscatedNazi propaganda is an English

1124
01:21:38,862 --> 01:21:42,344
language version of themotion picture [non-english],

1125
01:21:42,448 --> 01:21:45,034
"Baptism of Fire,"
showing the horror

1126
01:21:45,137 --> 01:21:47,827
and detailing the techniqueof the Blitzkrieg.

1127
01:21:47,931 --> 01:21:50,310
Hitler used this
film to soften up

1128
01:21:50,413 --> 01:21:52,551
resistance in the
European nations

1129
01:21:52,655 --> 01:21:54,413
he was about to destroy.

1130
01:21:54,517 --> 01:21:58,413
[trumpets]

1131
01:22:08,931 --> 01:22:13,206
The appointed hour is at hand.

1132
01:22:13,310 --> 01:22:16,206
The attack is geared
for lightening swiftness

1133
01:22:16,310 --> 01:22:17,655
and irresistible power.

1134
01:22:17,758 --> 01:22:21,758
Total war is a sciencewhich Germany has mastered.

1135
01:22:30,034 --> 01:22:33,517
The operation is directed fromthe Fuehrer's private railway

1136
01:22:33,620 --> 01:22:38,655
carriage, for the Fuehrerhimself is the final source

1137
01:22:38,758 --> 01:22:39,655
of all decisions and commands.

1138
01:22:44,586 --> 01:22:47,655
The orders go out to the variousdivisions and commanders,

1139
01:22:47,758 --> 01:22:50,482
assuring perfectcoordination of the attack.

1140
01:22:55,758 --> 01:22:58,793
The first units tocontact the enemy of those

1141
01:22:58,896 --> 01:23:01,620
of the German air force.

1142
01:23:01,724 --> 01:23:04,758
The years of sacrifice todevelop this great air force

1143
01:23:04,862 --> 01:23:07,000
have not been in vain.

1144
01:23:07,103 --> 01:23:10,137
For thousands of planes willcarry the attack to every part

1145
01:23:10,241 --> 01:23:11,310
of the enemy territory.

1146
01:23:21,206 --> 01:23:24,689
[plane engines]

1147
01:23:26,620 --> 01:23:29,724
Stuka planes, protected
by German engineers,

1148
01:23:29,827 --> 01:23:32,379
dive thousands of feet
upon their targets.

1149
01:23:32,482 --> 01:23:35,689
[plane engines]

1150
01:23:39,517 --> 01:23:42,379
A Stuka pilot dives upon
a railroad junction.

1151
01:23:42,482 --> 01:23:46,310
To bomb the target, he aims hismachine directly down upon it.

1152
01:24:12,724 --> 01:24:16,620
[explosion]

1153
01:24:20,620 --> 01:24:24,379
The task of the air
force in total war

1154
01:24:24,482 --> 01:24:28,344
is to attack enemy airfields anddisperse enemy concentrations

1155
01:24:28,448 --> 01:24:32,206
of troops and material, todisrupt enemy communications

1156
01:24:32,310 --> 01:24:36,344
far behind the lines, andto destroy the enemy's

1157
01:24:36,448 --> 01:24:37,896
vital industrial centers.

1158
01:24:41,586 --> 01:24:44,206
[explosions]

1159
01:24:44,310 --> 01:24:47,931
Against aircraft, suchantiquated weapons as armor

1160
01:24:48,034 --> 01:24:51,103
trains are utterly useless.

1161
01:24:56,413 --> 01:25:00,172
Because mastery of the air isvital to the lightning attack,

1162
01:25:00,275 --> 01:25:03,827
airports, multi-million
and military,

1163
01:25:03,931 --> 01:25:05,413
are among our first objectives.

1164
01:25:11,724 --> 01:25:15,448
But in a few days, theinferior air force of the enemy

1165
01:25:15,551 --> 01:25:20,000
has been completely destroyed,and the German air force rules

1166
01:25:20,103 --> 01:25:22,931
supreme.

1167
01:25:23,034 --> 01:25:24,724
To halt the advance
of our forces,

1168
01:25:24,827 --> 01:25:27,931
the enemy has blown
up his bridges.

1169
01:25:31,758 --> 01:25:35,172
But detachments of engineers,assisted by Reich labor

1170
01:25:35,275 --> 01:25:39,413
servicemen restore without delayany roads or bridges rendered

1171
01:25:39,517 --> 01:25:41,586
impassable by the enemy.

1172
01:25:41,689 --> 01:25:44,482
And our troops continuetheir advance unhindered.

1173
01:25:47,379 --> 01:25:51,448
[galloping]

1174
01:26:01,793 --> 01:26:05,275
The lightning attack demands theacceleration of all movements.

1175
01:26:05,379 --> 01:26:08,137
If bridges are
scarce, German forces,

1176
01:26:08,241 --> 01:26:12,068
even heavy mechanized units,have ways of crossing rivers

1177
01:26:12,172 --> 01:26:14,551
without them.

1178
01:26:14,655 --> 01:26:17,551
[engines]

1179
01:26:23,931 --> 01:26:28,034
Meanwhile, parachute troopsare dropped behind the lines.

1180
01:26:28,137 --> 01:26:31,689
These men are able to capturestrategic telephone, telegraph,

1181
01:26:31,793 --> 01:26:36,068
and wireless stations, andcause great panic and confusion,

1182
01:26:36,172 --> 01:26:39,689
particularly among civilians.

1183
01:26:39,793 --> 01:26:42,724
[plane engine]

1184
01:26:42,827 --> 01:26:45,793
Ranging far ahead of the mainbody of the army, [inaudible]

1185
01:26:45,896 --> 01:26:50,034
divisions, small, mechanized,highly mobile units

1186
01:26:50,137 --> 01:26:52,310
that penetrated to
enemy cities far

1187
01:26:52,413 --> 01:26:54,551
behind the main battle front.

1188
01:26:54,655 --> 01:26:56,000
[explosions]

1189
01:26:56,103 --> 01:26:58,206
If the surprised enemy garrisoncannot be overcome with hand

1190
01:26:58,310 --> 01:27:01,620
grenades and light
artillery, their hiding

1191
01:27:01,724 --> 01:27:03,586
place is sprayed with gasoline.

1192
01:27:06,344 --> 01:27:11,827
[gunfire]

1193
01:27:31,689 --> 01:27:35,620
The infantry follows themechanized divisions to destroy

1194
01:27:35,724 --> 01:27:38,827
the main armies of the enemy.

1195
01:27:38,931 --> 01:27:43,103
Hardened by long training,
the German soldier has

1196
01:27:43,206 --> 01:27:44,448
incredible physical endurance.

1197
01:27:47,724 --> 01:27:53,206
Sometimes, he must advance 30or 35 miles a day, with no rest

1198
01:27:53,310 --> 01:27:55,517
and little sleep for
more than a week.

1199
01:28:00,827 --> 01:28:02,448
The capital city
of the enemy nation

1200
01:28:02,551 --> 01:28:04,724
is reached within a few days.

1201
01:28:07,896 --> 01:28:09,827
When the enemy does notadopt the reasonable course

1202
01:28:09,931 --> 01:28:14,172
of unconditional surrender,
this capital must,

1203
01:28:14,275 --> 01:28:17,965
unfortunately, be destroyed.

1204
01:28:18,068 --> 01:28:22,482
[engine]

1205
01:28:33,689 --> 01:28:36,551
Nations which make
war upon Germany

1206
01:28:36,655 --> 01:28:39,896
must be prepared to face theconsequences of their acts.

1207
01:28:43,172 --> 01:28:47,586
The enemy at last has noalternative but surrender.

1208
01:29:04,517 --> 01:29:06,862
Because of his
senseless resistance,

1209
01:29:06,965 --> 01:29:09,896
the terms will now
be less lenient.

1210
01:29:10,000 --> 01:29:12,758
There is no possibility
of compromise

1211
01:29:12,862 --> 01:29:14,000
with the victorious German army.

1212
01:29:31,931 --> 01:29:35,827
Vast quantities of war materialsof all kinds of been captured,

1213
01:29:35,931 --> 01:29:38,551
more than enough to
replace what has been

1214
01:29:38,655 --> 01:29:42,068
lost for the German forces.

1215
01:29:42,172 --> 01:29:45,586
[orchestral music]

1216
01:29:52,137 --> 01:29:54,724
Within the city, German
soldiers are greeted

1217
01:29:54,827 --> 01:29:57,068
by loyal friends and admirers.

1218
01:29:57,172 --> 01:30:00,068
And every country,Germany has such friends.

1219
01:30:00,172 --> 01:30:01,689
[applause]

1220
01:30:01,793 --> 01:30:04,758
Those who have been of serviceto Germany behind enemy lines

1221
01:30:04,862 --> 01:30:07,620
are given an
opportunity to identify

1222
01:30:07,724 --> 01:30:12,034
persons who have persecutedthem before the German conquest.

1223
01:30:12,137 --> 01:30:14,000
Such persons will be shot.

1224
01:30:24,793 --> 01:30:28,827
As a result of their mad desireto wage war upon Germany,

1225
01:30:28,931 --> 01:30:32,310
hundreds of thousands of theenemy's most able-bodied men

1226
01:30:32,413 --> 01:30:35,586
have temporarily
lost their freedom.

1227
01:30:35,689 --> 01:30:37,931
They will be formed
into labor battalions

1228
01:30:38,034 --> 01:30:40,758
and sent to Germany to
help with the harvests,

1229
01:30:40,862 --> 01:30:43,206
and otherwise, to take theplace of German fighters

1230
01:30:43,310 --> 01:30:44,896
on other fronts.

1231
01:30:45,000 --> 01:30:47,827
Under German supervision,many of these men

1232
01:30:47,931 --> 01:30:51,620
will do useful work for thefirst time in their lives.

1233
01:31:04,586 --> 01:31:06,517
The enemy is no more.

1234
01:31:26,344 --> 01:31:30,827
Before the power of German armsand the terror of propaganda,

1235
01:31:30,931 --> 01:31:33,586
nine once-free nationshave already fallen under

1236
01:31:33,689 --> 01:31:36,034
the domination of Adolf Hitter.

1237
01:31:36,137 --> 01:31:40,793
And upon German conquest,Hitler has set no limits.

1238
01:31:40,896 --> 01:31:44,103
The slogan of his war
machine-- today, we

1239
01:31:44,206 --> 01:31:45,551
are masters of Europe.

1240
01:31:45,655 --> 01:31:50,034
Tomorrow, we shall
rule the world.

1241
01:31:50,137 --> 01:31:51,931
[speaking german]

1242
01:32:19,862 --> 01:32:24,689
Again, today, as in the
years of 1917 and '18,

1243
01:32:24,793 --> 01:32:27,620
the American people arepreparing to meet the challenge

1244
01:32:27,724 --> 01:32:31,586
of might makes right.

1245
01:32:31,689 --> 01:32:37,344
Overwhelmingly, we as a
nation, we are convinced

1246
01:32:37,448 --> 01:32:44,827
that military and naval victoryfor the gods of force of hate,

1247
01:32:44,931 --> 01:32:47,724
would endanger theinstitutions of democracy

1248
01:32:47,827 --> 01:32:50,724
in the Western world.

1249
01:32:50,827 --> 01:32:54,034
Once more, the
future of the nation,

1250
01:32:54,137 --> 01:33:00,206
the future of the Americanpeople, is at stake.

1251
01:33:00,310 --> 01:33:09,241
I call for effort, courage,sacrifice, [inaudible],

1252
01:33:09,344 --> 01:33:14,724
granting the love of freedom,All of these are possible.

1253
01:33:17,275 --> 01:33:24,310
And the love freedom isstill fierce, still steady,

1254
01:33:24,413 --> 01:33:27,310
in the nation today.

1255
01:33:27,413 --> 01:33:31,206
[applause]

1256
01:33:34,655 --> 01:33:37,275
[patriotic music]

1257
01:33:43,620 --> 01:33:46,413
Our way of life
is in competition

1258
01:33:46,517 --> 01:33:48,379
with Hitler's way of life.

1259
01:33:48,482 --> 01:33:50,896
And I promise to
out-distance him

1260
01:33:51,000 --> 01:33:53,758
in any contest he may choose.

1261
01:33:53,862 --> 01:33:56,862
And I promise you
that when we beat him,

1262
01:33:56,965 --> 01:34:01,068
we will beat him on our ownterms, and in the American way.

1263
01:34:01,172 --> 01:34:04,000
[applause]

1264
01:34:18,413 --> 01:34:21,793
NARRATOR: Today under leadersunited in their determination

1265
01:34:21,896 --> 01:34:25,206
to meet force withsuperior force, Americans

1266
01:34:25,310 --> 01:34:29,068
themselves once more standunited against the powers

1267
01:34:29,172 --> 01:34:30,793
of aggression.

1268
01:34:30,896 --> 01:34:34,000
And as Americans measure
their nation's strength,

1269
01:34:34,103 --> 01:34:37,000
they remember that there havebeen other times of crisis

1270
01:34:37,103 --> 01:34:39,931
when the people of Americahave taken up arms.

1271
01:34:40,034 --> 01:34:42,758
The founders of America
fought for freedom

1272
01:34:42,862 --> 01:34:46,103
and established theirrepublic by force of arms.

1273
01:34:46,206 --> 01:34:50,310
Other generations of Americanshave fought to preserve it,

1274
01:34:50,413 --> 01:34:53,275
and Americans today rememberthat their nation's courage

1275
01:34:53,379 --> 01:34:56,241
has been tested under fire
within the memory of men

1276
01:34:56,344 --> 01:34:57,827
now living.

1277
01:34:57,931 --> 01:34:58,724
MAN: Happy New Year!

1278
01:34:58,827 --> 01:35:01,000
[cheering]

1279
01:35:01,103 --> 01:35:04,620
NARRATOR: For in their
brave little world,

1280
01:35:04,724 --> 01:35:06,862
Americans of a
generation ago met

1281
01:35:06,965 --> 01:35:10,724
crisis, and emerged fromit citizens of the greatest

1282
01:35:10,827 --> 01:35:12,965
nation on Earth.

1283
01:35:13,068 --> 01:35:15,413
Now, an old man, I'd
like to make a toast.

1284
01:35:19,068 --> 01:35:24,517
Through the generations
yet to come, in peace,

1285
01:35:24,620 --> 01:35:30,034
may they cherish that which weare handing on down to them.

1286
01:35:30,137 --> 01:35:34,827
In crisis, may
they unite and know

1287
01:35:34,931 --> 01:35:39,793
as we have known the joy
and strength of uniting.

1288
01:35:42,689 --> 01:35:47,137
In war, if it should
ever come again,

1289
01:35:47,241 --> 01:35:53,482
may they hold the rampartsof our democracy and freedom

1290
01:35:53,586 --> 01:35:56,965
until kingdom come.

1291
01:35:57,068 --> 01:35:58,172
[MUSIC - "THE STAR SPANGLED BANNER"]

1292
01:35:58,275 --> 01:36:00,000
CHORUS: --the
rockets' red glare,

1293
01:36:00,103 --> 01:36:09,862
the bombs bursting in air,gave proof through the night

1294
01:36:09,965 --> 01:36:15,655
that our flag was still there.

1295
01:36:15,758 --> 01:36:32,310
Oh, say, does that star-spangledbanner yet wave o'er the land

1296
